# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: conning-tower
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Most modern anti-aircraft (AA) weapons systems are optimised for short-, medium-, or long-range air defence, although some systems may incorporate multiple weapons (such as both autocannons and surface-to-air missiles).
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] 'Layered air defence' usually refers to multiple 'tiers' of air defence systems which, when combined, an airborne threat must penetrate to reach its target; this defence is usually accomplished via the combined use of systems optimised for either short-, medium-, or long-range air defence.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] In some countries, such as Britain and Germany during the Second World War, the Soviet Union, and modern NATO and the United States, ground-based air defence and air defence aircraft have been under integrated command and control.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] However, while overall air defence may be for homeland defence (including military facilities), forces in the field, wherever they are, provide their own defences against airborne threats.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] It may also be called *counter-air*, *anti-air*, *AA*, *flak*, *layered air defence* or *air defence forces*.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] The term *air defence* was probably first used by the UK when Air Defence of Great Britain (ADGB) was created as a Royal Air Force command in 1925.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] However, arrangements in the UK were also called *anti-aircraft*, abbreviated as *AA*, a term that remained in general use into the 1950s.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] After the First World War it was sometimes prefixed by "light" or "heavy" (*LAA* or *HAA*) to classify a type of gun or unit.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] NATO defines anti-aircraft warfare (AAW) as "measures taken to defend a maritime force against attacks by airborne weapons launched from aircraft, ships, submarines and land-based sites".
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] In some armies the term *all-arms air defence* (AAAD) is used for air defence by nonspecialist troops.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Other terms from the late 20th century include "ground based air defence" (GBAD) with related terms "short range air defence" (SHORAD) and man-portable air-defence system (MANPADS).
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Anti-aircraft missiles are variously called surface-to-air missiles, ("SAMs") and surface-to-air guided weapons (SAGWs).
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Examples are the RIM-66 Standard, Raytheon Standard Missile 6, or the MBDA Aster missile.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Non-English terms for air defence include the German term *Flak* or *FlaK* (*Fliegerabwehrkanone*, lit.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] 'aircraft defence cannon', also cited as *Flugabwehrkanone*), and the Russian term *Protivovozdushnaya oborona* (Russian: Противовозду́шная оборо́на, lit.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] 'anti-air defence'), abbreviated as PVO.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] In Russian, the AA systems are called *zenitnye* (i.e., 'pointing to zenith') systems.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] In French, air defence is called *Défense contre les aéronefs (DCA)*, lit.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] The maximum distance at which a gun or missile can engage an aircraft is an important figure.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] However, many different definitions are used and unless the same definition is used, performance of different guns or missiles cannot be compared.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] For AA guns only the ascending part of the trajectory can be usefully used.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] One term is "ceiling", the maximum ceiling being the height a projectile would reach if fired vertically, not practically useful in itself as few AA guns are able to fire vertically, and the maximum fuse duration may be too short, but potentially useful as a standard to compare different weapons.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] The British adopted "effective ceiling", meaning the altitude at which a gun could deliver a series of shells against a moving target; this could be constrained by maximum fuse running time as well as the gun's capability.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] By the late 1930s the British definition was "that height at which a directly approaching target at 400 mph [640 km/h] can be engaged for 20 seconds before the gun reaches 70 degrees elevation".
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] The essence of air defence is to detect hostile aircraft and destroy them.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] The critical issue is to hit a target moving in three-dimensional space; an attack must not only match these three coordinates, but must do so at the time the target is at that position.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] This means that projectiles either have to be guided to hit the target, or aimed at the predicted position of the target at the time the projectile reaches it, taking into account the speed and direction of both the target and the projectile.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Improvements were made to sensors, technical fire control, weapons, and command and control.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] At the start of the 20th century these were either very primitive or non-existent.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Initially sensors were optical and acoustic devices developed during World War I and continued into the 1930s, but were quickly superseded by radar, which in turn was supplemented by optoelectronics in the 1980s.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Command and control remained primitive until the late 1930s, when Britain created the integrated Dowding system for ADGB that linked the ground-based air defence of the British Army's Anti-Aircraft Command, although field-deployed air defence relied on less sophisticated arrangements.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] NATO later called these arrangements an "air defence ground environment", defined as "the network of ground radar sites and command and control centres within a specific theatre of operations which are used for the tactical control of air defence operations".
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Rules of engagement are critical to prevent air defences engaging friendly or neutral aircraft.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Their use is assisted but not governed by identification friend or foe (IFF) electronic devices originally introduced during the Second World War.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] While these rules originate at the highest authority, different rules can apply to different types of air defence covering the same area at the same time.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] AAAD usually operates under the tightest rules.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Until the 1950s, guns firing ballistic munitions were the standard weapon; guided missiles then became dominant, except at the very shortest ranges.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] However, the type of shell or warhead and its fuzing and, with missiles, the guidance arrangement were and are varied.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Targets are not always easy to destroy; nonetheless, damaged aircraft may be forced to abort their mission and, even if they manage to return and land in friendly territory, may be out of action for days or permanently.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Ignoring small arms and smaller machine-guns, ground-based air defence guns have varied in caliber from 20 mm to at least 152 mm.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Passive air defence is defined by NATO as "Passive measures taken for the physical defence and protection of personnel, essential installations and equipment in order to minimise the effectiveness of air and/or missile attack".
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] It remains a vital activity by ground forces and includes camouflage and concealment to avoid detection by reconnaissance and attacking aircraft.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Measures such as camouflaging important buildings were common in the Second World War.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] During the Cold War the runways and taxiways of some airfields were painted green.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] While navies are usually responsible for their own air defence—at least for ships at sea—organisational arrangements for land-based air defence vary between nations and over time.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] The most extreme case was the Soviet Union and this model may still be followed in some countries: it was a separate service, on a par with the army, navy, or air force.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] In the Soviet Union, this was called *Voyska PVO*, and had both fighter aircraft, separate from the air force, and ground-based systems.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] This was divided into two arms, *PVO Strany,* the Strategic Air defence Service responsible for Air Defence of the Homeland, created in 1941 and becoming an independent service in 1954, and *PVO SV,* Air Defence of the Ground Forces.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Subsequently, these became part of the air force and ground forces respectively.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] At the other extreme, the United States Army has an Air Defense Artillery Branch that provides ground-based air defence for both homeland and the army in the field; however, it is operationally under the Joint Force Air Component Commander.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Many other nations also deploy an air-defence branch in the army.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Some, such as Japan or Israel, choose to integrate their ground based air defence systems into their air force.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] In Britain and some other armies, the single artillery branch has been responsible for both home and overseas ground-based air defence, although there was divided responsibility with the Royal Navy for air defence of the British Isles in World War I.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] However, during the Second World War, the RAF Regiment was formed to protect airfields everywhere, and this included light air defences.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] In the later decades of the Cold War this included the United States Air Force's operating bases in the UK.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] All ground-based air defence was removed from Royal Air Force (RAF) jurisdiction in 2004.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] The British Army's Anti-Aircraft Command was disbanded in March 1955, but during the 1960s and 1970s the RAF's Fighter Command operated long-range air-defence missiles to protect key areas in the UK.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] During World War II, the Royal Marines also provided air defence units; formally part of the mobile naval base defence organisation, they were handled as an integral part of the army-commanded ground based air defences.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] The basic air defence unit is typically a battery with 2 to 12 guns or missile launchers and fire control elements.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] These batteries, particularly with guns, usually deploy in a small area, although batteries may be split; this is usual for some missile systems.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] SHORAD missile batteries often deploy across an area with individual launchers several kilometres apart.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] When MANPADS is operated by specialists, batteries may have several dozen teams deploying separately in small sections; self-propelled air defence guns may deploy in pairs.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Batteries are usually grouped into battalions or equivalent.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] In the field army, a light gun or SHORAD battalion is often assigned to a manoeuvre division.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Heavier guns and long-range missiles may be in air-defence brigades and come under corps or higher command.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] Homeland air defence may have a full military structure.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] For example, the UK's Anti-Aircraft Command, commanded by a full British Army general was part of ADGB.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p01] At its peak in 1941–42 it comprised three AA corps with 12 AA divisions between them.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Army during the American Civil War compelled the Confederates to develop methods of combating them.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] These included the use of artillery, small arms, and saboteurs.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] They were unsuccessful, and internal politics led the United States Army's Balloon Corps to be disbanded mid-war.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The Confederates experimented with balloons as well.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Turks carried out the first ever anti-airplane operation in history during the Italo-Turkish War.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Although lacking anti-aircraft weapons, they were the first to shoot down an airplane by rifle fire.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The first aircraft to crash in a war was the one of Lieutenant Piero Manzini, shot down on 25 August 1912.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The earliest known use of weapons specifically made for the anti-aircraft role occurred during the Franco-Prussian War of 1870.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] After the disaster at Sedan, Paris was besieged and French troops outside the city started an attempt at communication via balloon.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Gustav Krupp mounted a modified 1-pounder (37 mm) gun – the *Ballonabwehrkanone* (Balloon defence cannon) or *BaK* — on top of a horse-drawn carriage for the purpose of shooting down these balloons.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] By the early 20th century balloon, or airship, guns, for land and naval use were attracting attention.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Various types of ammunition were proposed, high explosive, incendiary, bullet-chains, rod bullets and shrapnel.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The need for some form of tracer or smoke trail was articulated.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Fuzing options were also examined, both impact and time types.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Mountings were generally pedestal type but could be on field platforms.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Trials were underway in most countries in Europe but only Krupp, Erhardt, Vickers Maxim, and Schneider had published any information by 1910.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Krupp's designs included adaptations of their 65 mm 9-pounder, a 75 mm 12-pounder, and even a 105 mm gun.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Erhardt also had a 12-pounder, while Vickers Maxim offered a 3-pounder and Schneider a 47 mm.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The French balloon gun appeared in 1910, it was an 11-pounder but mounted on a vehicle, with a total uncrewed weight of two tons.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] However, since balloons were slow moving, sights were simple.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] But the challenges of faster moving aeroplanes were recognised.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] By 1913 only France and Germany had developed field guns suitable for engaging balloons and aircraft and addressed issues of military organisation.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Britain's Royal Navy would soon introduce the QF 3-inch and QF 4-inch AA guns and also had Vickers 1-pounder quick firing "pom-poms" that could be used in various mountings.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The first US anti-aircraft cannon was a 1-pounder concept design by Admiral Twining in 1911 to meet the perceived threat of airships, that eventually was used as the basis for the US Navy's first operational anti-aircraft cannon: the 3-inch/23 caliber gun.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] On 30 September 1915, troops of the Serbian Army observed three enemy aircraft approaching Kragujevac.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Soldiers fired at them with shotguns and machine-guns but failed to prevent them from dropping 45 bombs over the city, hitting military installations, the railway station and many other, mostly civilian, targets in the city.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] During the bombing raid, private Radoje Ljutovac fired his cannon at the enemy aircraft and successfully shot one down.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] It crashed in the city and both pilots died from their injuries.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The cannon Ljutovac used was not designed as an anti-aircraft gun; it was a slightly modified Turkish cannon captured during the First Balkan War in 1912.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] This was the first occasion in military history that a military aircraft was shot down with ground-to-air artillery fire.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] By December 1914 the Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve (RNVR) was manning AA guns and searchlights assembled from various sources at some nine ports.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The Royal Garrison Artillery (RGA) was given responsibility for AA defence in the field, using motorised two-gun sections.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The first were formally formed in November 1914.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Initially they used QF 1-pounder "pom-pom"s (37 mm versions of the Maxim Gun).
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] All armies soon deployed AA guns often based on their smaller field pieces, notably the French 75 mm and Russian 76.2 mm, typically simply propped up on some sort of embankment to get the muzzle pointed skyward.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The British Army adopted the 13-pounder quickly producing new mountings suitable for AA use, the 13-pounder QF 6 cwt Mk III was issued in 1915.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] It remained in service throughout the war but 18-pounder guns were lined down to take the 13-pounder shell with a larger cartridge producing the 13-pounder QF 9 cwt and these proved much more satisfactory.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] However, in general, these ad hoc solutions proved largely useless.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] With little experience in the role, no means of measuring target, range, height or speed the difficulty of observing their shell bursts relative to the target gunners proved unable to get their fuse setting correct and most rounds burst well below their targets.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The exception to this rule was the guns protecting spotting balloons, in which case the altitude could be accurately measured from the length of the cable holding the balloon.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Before the war it was recognised that ammunition needed to explode in the air.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Both high explosive (HE) and shrapnel were used, mostly the former.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Airburst fuses were either igniferious (based on a burning fuse) or mechanical (clockwork).
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Igniferious fuses were not well suited for anti-aircraft use.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The fuse length was determined by time of flight, but the burning rate of the gunpowder was affected by altitude.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The British pom-poms had only contact-fused ammunition.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Zeppelins, being hydrogen-filled balloons, were targets for incendiary shells and the British introduced these with airburst fuses, both shrapnel type-forward projection of incendiary "pot" and base ejection of an incendiary stream.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The British also fitted tracers to their shells for use at night.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Smoke shells were also available for some AA guns, these bursts were used as targets during training.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] German air attacks on the British Isles increased in 1915 and the AA efforts were deemed somewhat ineffective, so a Royal Navy gunnery expert, Admiral Sir Percy Scott, was appointed to make improvements, particularly an integrated AA defence for London.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The air defences were expanded with more RNVR AA guns, 75 mm and 3-inch, the pom-poms being ineffective.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The naval 3-inch was also adopted by the army, the QF 3-inch 20 cwt (76 mm), a new field mounting was introduced in 1916.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Since most attacks were at night, searchlights were soon used, and acoustic methods of detection and locating were developed.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] By December 1916 there were 183 AA sections defending Britain (most with the 3-inch), 74 with the BEF in France and 10 in the Middle East.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The problem was of successfully aiming a shell to burst close to its target's future position, with various factors affecting the shells' predicted trajectory.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] This was called deflection gun-laying, where "off-set" angles for range and elevation were set on the gunsight and updated as their target moved.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In this method, when the sights were on the target, the barrel was pointed at the target's future position.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Range and height of the target determined fuse length.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The difficulties increased as aircraft performance improved.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The British dealt with range measurement first, when it was realised that range was the key to producing a better fuse setting.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] This led to the height/range finder (HRF), the first model being the Barr & Stroud UB2, a two-metre optical coincident rangefinder mounted on a tripod.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] It measured the distance to the target and the elevation angle, which together gave the height of the aircraft.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] These were complex instruments and various other methods were also used.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The HRF was soon joined by the height/fuse indicator (HFI), this was marked with elevation angles and height lines overlaid with fuse length curves, using the height reported by the HRF operator, the necessary fuse length could be read off.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] However, the problem of deflection settings — "aim-off" — required knowing the rate of change in the target's position.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Both France and the UK introduced tachymetric devices to track targets and produce vertical and horizontal deflection angles.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The French Brocq system was electrical; the operator entered the target range and had displays at guns; it was used with their 75 mm.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The British Wilson-Dalby gun director used a pair of trackers and mechanical tachymetry; the operator entered the fuse length, and deflection angles were read from the instruments.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] By the start of World War I, the 77 mm had become the standard German weapon, and came mounted on a large traverse that could be easily transported on a wagon.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Krupp 75 mm guns were supplied with an optical sighting system that improved their capabilities.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The German Army also adapted a revolving cannon that came to be known to Allied fliers as the "flaming onion" from the shells in flight.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] This gun had five barrels that quickly launched a series of 37 mm artillery shells.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] As aircraft started to be used against ground targets on the battlefield, the AA guns could not be traversed quickly enough at close targets and, being relatively few, were not always in the right place (and were often unpopular with other troops), so changed positions frequently.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Soon the forces were adding various machine-gun based weapons mounted on poles.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] These short-range weapons proved more deadly, and the "Red Baron" is believed to have been shot down by an anti-aircraft Vickers machine gun.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] When the war ended, it was clear that the increasing capabilities of aircraft would require better means of acquiring targets and aiming at them.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Nevertheless, a pattern had been set: anti-aircraft warfare would employ heavy weapons to attack high-altitude targets and lighter weapons for use when aircraft came to lower altitudes.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] World War I demonstrated that aircraft could be an important part of the battlefield, but in some nations it was the prospect of strategic air attack that was the main issue, presenting both a threat and an opportunity.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The experience of four years of air attacks on London by Zeppelins and Gotha G.V bombers had particularly influenced the British and was one of if not the main driver for forming an independent air force.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] As the capabilities of aircraft and their engines improved it was clear that their role in future war would be even more critical as their range and weapon load grew.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] However, in the years immediately after World War I, the prospect of another major war seemed remote, particularly in Europe, where the most militarily capable nations were, and little financing was available.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Four years of war had seen the creation of a new and technically demanding branch of military activity.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Air defence had made huge advances, albeit from a very low starting point.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] However, it was new and often lacked influential 'friends' in the competition for a share of limited defence budgets.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Demobilisation meant that most AA guns were taken out of service, leaving only the most modern.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] However, there were lessons to be learned.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In particular the British, who had had AA guns in most theatres in action in daylight and used them against night attacks at home.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Furthermore, they had also formed an Anti-Aircraft Experimental Section during the war and accumulated large amounts of data that was subjected to extensive analysis.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] As a result, they published the two-volume *Textbook of Anti-Aircraft Gunnery* in 1924–1925.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Two assumptions underpinned the British approach to HAA fire; first, aimed fire was the primary method and this was enabled by predicting gun data from visually tracking the target and having its height.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Second, that the target would maintain a steady course, speed and height.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] This HAA was to engage targets up to 24,000 ft (7.3 km).
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Mechanical time fuses were required because the speed of powder burning varied with height, so fuse length was not a simple function of time of flight.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Automated fire ensured a constant rate of fire that made it easier to predict where each shell should be individually aimed.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In 1925 the British adopted a new instrument developed by Vickers.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] It was a mechanical analogue computer – the Predictor AA No 1.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Given the target height, its operators tracked the target and the predictor produced bearing, quadrant elevation and fuse setting.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] These were passed electrically to the guns, where they were displayed on repeater dials to the layers who "matched pointers" (target data and the gun's actual data) to lay the guns.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] This system of repeater electrical dials built on the arrangements introduced by British coast artillery in the 1880s, and coast artillery was the background of many AA officers.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Similar systems were adopted in other countries and for example the later Sperry M3A3 in the US, was also used by Britain as the Predictor AA No 2.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Height finders were also increasing in size; in Britain, the 7 ft (2.1 m) optical base World War I Barr & Stroud UB 2 stereoscopic rangefinder was replaced by the 9 ft (2.7 m) optical base UB 7 and the 18 ft (5.5 m) base UB 10 (only used on static AA sites).
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Goertz in Germany and Levallois in France produced five-metre (16 ft) instruments.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] However, in most countries the main effort in HAA guns until the mid-1930s was improving existing ones, although various new designs were on drawing boards.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] From the early 1930s eight countries developed radar; these developments were sufficiently advanced by the late 1930s for development work on sound-locating acoustic devices to be generally halted, although equipment was retained.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Furthermore, in Britain the volunteer Observer Corps formed in 1925 provided a network of observation posts to report hostile aircraft flying over Britain.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Initially radar was used for airspace surveillance to detect approaching hostile aircraft.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] However, the German Würzburg radar put into use in 1940 was capable of providing data suitable for controlling AA guns, and the British Radar, Gun Laying, Mark I, was designed to be used on AA gun positions and was in use by 1939.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The Treaty of Versailles prevented Germany having AA weapons, and for example, the Krupps designers joined Bofors in Sweden.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Some World War I guns were retained and some covert AA training started in the late 1920s.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Germany introduced the 8.8 cm FlaK 18 in 1933, the 36 and 37 models followed with various improvements, but ballistic performance was unchanged.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In the late 1930s the 10.5 cm FlaK 38 appeared, soon followed by the 39; this was designed primarily for static sites but had a mobile mounting, and the unit had 220 V 24 kW generators.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In 1938 design started on the 12.8 cm FlaK.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Britain had successfully tested a new 3.6-inch gun, in 1918.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In 1928 a 3.7-inch (94 mm) gun became the preferred solution, but it took six years to gain funding.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Production of the QF 3.7-inch gun began in 1937; this gun was used on mobile carriages with the field army and transportable guns on fixed mountings for static positions.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] At the same time the Royal Navy adopted a new 4.5-inch (113 mm) gun in a twin turret, which the army adopted in simplified single-gun mountings for static positions, mostly around ports where naval ammunition was available.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The performance of the new guns was limited by their standard fuse No 199, with a 30-second running time, although a new mechanical time fuse giving 43 seconds was nearing readiness.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In 1939 a machine fuse setter was introduced to eliminate manual fuse setting.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The US ended World War I with two 3-inch AA guns and improvements were developed throughout the inter-war period.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] However, in 1924 work started on a new 105 mm static mounting AA gun, but only a few were produced by the mid-1930s because by this time work had started on the 90 mm AA gun, with mobile carriages and static mountings able to engage air, sea and ground targets.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] During the 1920s there was some work on a 4.7-inch which lapsed, but revived in 1937, leading to a new gun in 1944.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] While HAA and its associated target acquisition and fire control was the primary focus of AA efforts, low-level close-range targets remained and by the mid-1930s were becoming an issue.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Until this time the British, at RAF insistence, continued their use of World War I machine guns, and introduced twin MG mountings for AAAD.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The army was forbidden from considering anything larger than .50-inch.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] However, in 1935 their trials showed that the minimum effective round was an impact-fused 2 lb HE shell.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The following year they decided to adopt the Bofors 40 mm and a twin barrel Vickers 2-pounder (40 mm) on a modified naval mount.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The air-cooled Bofors was vastly superior for land use, being much lighter than the water-cooled "pom-pom", and UK production of the Bofors 40 mm was licensed.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The Predictor AA No 3, as the Kerrison Predictor was officially known, was introduced with it.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The 40 mm Bofors had become available in 1931.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In the late 1920s the Swedish Navy had ordered the development of a 40 mm naval anti-aircraft gun from the Bofors company.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] It was light, rapid-firing and reliable, and a mobile version on a four-wheel carriage was soon developed.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Known simply as the 40 mm, it was adopted by some 17 different nations just before World War II and is still in use today in some applications such as on coastguard frigates.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Rheinmetall in Germany developed an automatic 20 mm in the 1920s and Oerlikon in Switzerland had acquired the patent to an automatic 20 mm gun designed in Germany during World War I.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Germany introduced the rapid-fire 2 cm FlaK 30 and later in the decade it was redesigned by Mauser-Werke and became the 2 cm FlaK 38.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Nevertheless, while 20 mm was better than a machine gun and mounted on a very small trailer made it easy to move, its effectiveness was limited.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The first, the 3.7 cm FlaK 18 developed by Rheinmetall in the early 1930s, was basically an enlarged 2 cm FlaK 30.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] It was introduced in 1935 and production stopped the following year.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] A redesigned gun 3.7 cm FlaK 36 entered service in 1938, it too had a two-wheel carriage.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] However, by the mid-1930s the Luftwaffe realised that there was still a coverage gap between 3.7 cm and 8.8 cm guns.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] They started development of a 5 cm gun on a four-wheel carriage.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] After World War I the US Army started developing a dual-role (AA/ground) automatic 37 mm cannon, designed by John M.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] It was standardised in 1927 as the T9 AA cannon, but trials quickly revealed that it was worthless in the ground role.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] However, while the shell was a bit light (well under 2 lbs) it had a good effective ceiling and fired 125 rounds per minute; an AA carriage was developed and it entered service in 1939 as the 37 mm gun M1.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] It proved prone to jamming, and was eventually replaced in AA units by the Bofors 40 mm.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The Bofors had attracted attention from the US Navy, but none were acquired before 1939.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Also, in 1931 the US Army worked on a mobile anti-aircraft machine mount on the back of a heavy truck having four .30 calibre water-cooled machine guns and an optical director.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] It proved unsuccessful and was abandoned.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The USSR introduced a new 76 mm *M1931* in 1937, an 85 mm *M1938* and developed the 37 mm M1939 (61-K), which appears to have been copied from the Bofors 40 mm.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] A Bofors 25 mm, essentially a scaled down 40 mm, was also copied as the 25 mm M1939.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] During the 1930s solid-fuel rockets were under development in the Soviet Union and Britain.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In Britain the interest was for anti-aircraft fire, it quickly became clear that guidance would be required for precision.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] However, rockets, or "Unrotated Projectiles" as they were called, could be used for anti-aircraft barrages.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] A two-inch rocket using HE or wire obstacle warheads – the Z Battery – was introduced first to deal with low-level or dive bombing attacks on smaller targets such as airfields.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The three-inch was in development at the end of the inter-war period.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] WWI had been a war in which air warfare blossomed, but had not matured to the point of being a real threat to naval forces.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The prevailing assumption was that a few relatively small caliber naval guns could manage to keep enemy aircraft beyond a range where harm might be expected.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In 1939 radio controlled target drones became available to the US Navy in quantity allowing a more realistic testing of existing anti-aircraft suites against actual flying and manoeuvring targets.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The results were sobering to an unexpected degree.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The United States was still emerging from the effects of the Great Depression and funds for the military had been sparse to the degree that 50% of shells used were still powder fused.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The US Navy found that a significant portion of its shells were duds or low order detonations (incomplete detonation of the explosive contained by the shell).
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Virtually every major country involved in combat in World War II invested in aircraft development.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The cost of aircraft research and development was small and the results could be large.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] So rapid was the performance leaps of evolving aircraft that the British High Angle Control System (HACS) was obsolete and designing a successor very difficult for the British establishment.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Electronics would prove to be an enabler for effective anti-aircraft systems and both the US and UK had a growing electronics industry.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In 1939 radio controlled drones became available to actually test existing systems in British and American service.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The results were disappointing by any measure.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] High-level manoeuvring drones were virtually immune to shipboard AA systems.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The US drones could simulate dive bombing which showed the dire need for autocannons.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Japan introduced powered gliders in 1940 as drones but apparently was unable to dive bomb.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] There is no evidence of other powers using drones in this application at all.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] It may have caused a major underestimation of the threat and an inflated view of their AA systems.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Poland's AA defences were no match for the German attack, and the situation was similar in other European countries.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Significant AAW (Anti-Air Warfare) started with the Battle of Britain in the summer of 1940.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] QF 3.7-inch AA guns provided the backbone of the ground-based AA defences, although initially significant numbers of QF 3-inch 20 cwt were also used.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The Army's Anti-aircraft command, which was under operational command of RAF Fighter Command within Air Defence GB, grew to 12 AA divisions in three AA corps.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Bofors 40 mm guns entered service in increasing numbers.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In addition, the RAF regiment was formed in 1941 with responsibility for airfield air defence, eventually with Bofors 40 mm as their main armament.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Fixed AA defences, using HAA and LAA, were established by the Army in key overseas places, notably Malta, Suez Canal and Singapore.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] While the 3.7-inch was the main HAA gun in fixed defences and the only mobile HAA gun with the field army, the QF 4.5-inch gun, manned by artillery, was used in the vicinity of naval ports and made use of the naval ammunition supply.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The 4.5-inch at Singapore had the first success in shooting down Japanese bombers.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Mid war QF 5.25-inch naval guns started being emplaced in some permanent sites around London.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] This gun was also deployed in dual-role coast defence/AA positions.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Germany's high-altitude needs were originally going to be filled by a 75 mm gun from Krupp, designed in collaboration with their Swedish counterpart Bofors, but the specifications were later amended to require much higher performance.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In response Krupp's engineers presented a new 88 mm design, the FlaK 36.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] First used in Spain during the Spanish Civil War, the gun proved to be one of the best anti-aircraft guns in the world, as well as particularly deadly against light, medium, and even early heavy tanks.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] After the Dambusters raid in 1943 an entirely new system was developed that was required to knock down any low-flying aircraft with a single hit.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The first attempt to produce such a system used a 50 mm gun, but this proved inaccurate and a new 55 mm gun replaced it.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The system used a centralised control system including both search and targeting radar, which calculated the aim point for the guns after considering windage and ballistics, and then sent electrical commands to the guns, which used hydraulics to point themselves at high speeds.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Operators simply fed the guns and selected the targets.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] This system, modern even by today's standards, was in late development when the war ended.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The British had already arranged licence building of the Bofors 40 mm, and introduced these into service.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] These had the power to knock down aircraft of any size, yet were light enough to be mobile and easily swung.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The gun became so important to the British war effort that they even produced a movie, *The Gun*, that encouraged workers on the assembly line to work harder.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The Imperial measurement production drawings the British had developed were supplied to the Americans who produced their own (unlicensed) copy of the 40 mm at the start of the war, moving to licensed production in mid-1941.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Service trials demonstrated another problem however: that ranging and tracking the new high-speed targets was almost impossible.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] At short range, the apparent target area is relatively large, the trajectory is flat and the time of flight is short, allowing to correct lead by watching the tracers.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] At long range, the aircraft remains in firing range for a long time, so the necessary calculations can, in theory, be done by slide rules—though, because small errors in distance cause large errors in shell fall height and detonation time, exact ranging is crucial.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] For the ranges and speeds that the Bofors worked at, neither answer was good enough.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The solution was automation, in the form of a mechanical computer, the Kerrison Predictor.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Operators kept it pointed at the target, and the Predictor then calculated the proper aim point automatically and displayed it as a pointer mounted on the gun.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The gun operators simply followed the pointer and loaded the shells.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The Kerrison was fairly simple, but it pointed the way to future generations that incorporated radar, first for ranging and later for tracking.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Similar predictor systems were introduced by Germany during the war, also adding radar ranging as the war progressed.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] A plethora of anti-aircraft gun systems of smaller calibre was available to the German Wehrmacht combined forces, and among them the 1940-origin *Flakvierling* quadruple-20 mm-autocannon-based anti-aircraft weapon system was one of the most often-seen weapons, seeing service on both land and sea.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The similar Allied smaller-calibre air-defence weapons of the American forces were also quite capable.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Although of less power than Germany's 20 mm systems, the typical four or five combat batteries of an Army AAA battalion were often spread many kilometres apart from each other, rapidly attaching and detaching to larger ground combat units to provide welcome defence from enemy aircraft.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] AAA battalions were also used to help suppress ground targets.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Their larger 90 mm M3 gun would prove, as did the eighty-eight, to make an excellent anti-tank gun as well, and was widely used late in the war in this role.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Also available to the Americans at the start of the war was the 120 mm M1 gun *stratosphere gun*, which was the most powerful AA gun with an impressive 60,000 ft (18 km) altitude capability, however no 120 M1 was ever fired at an enemy aircraft.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The 90 mm and 120 mm guns continued to be used into the 1950s.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The United States Navy had also put some thought into the problem, When the US Navy began to rearm in 1939 in many ships the primary short ranged gun was the M2 .50 caliber machine gun.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] While effective in fighters at 300 to 400 yards this is point blank range in naval anti-aircraft ranges.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Production of the Swiss Oerlikon 20 mm had already started to provide protection for the British and this was adopted in exchange for the M2 machine guns.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] From December 1941 to January 1942, production had risen to not only cover all British requirements but also allowed 812 units to be actually delivered to the US Navy.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] By the end of 1942 the 20 mm had accounted for 42% of all aircraft destroyed by the US Navy's shipboard AA.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] However, the King Board had noted that the balance was shifting towards the larger guns used by the fleet.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The US Navy had intended to use the British pom-pom, however, the weapon required the use of cordite which BuOrd had found objectionable for US service.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Further investigation revealed that US powders would not work in the pom-pom.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Bureau of Ordnance was well aware of the Bofors 40 mm gun.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The firm York Safe and Lock was negotiating with Bofors to attain the rights to the air-cooled version of the weapon.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] At the same time Henry Howard, an engineer, and businessman became aware of it and contacted RADM W.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Furlong, chief of the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] He ordered the Bofors weapon system to be investigated.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] York Safe and Lock would be used as the contracting agent.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The system had to be redesigned for both the English measurement system and mass production, as the original documents recommended hand fitting parts and drilling to shape.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] As early as 1928 the US Navy saw the need to replace the .50 caliber machine gun with something heavier.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Placed in quadruple mounts with a 500 rpm rate of fire it would have fit the requirements.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] However, the gun was suffering teething issues being prone to jamming.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] While this could have been solved the weight of the system was equal to that of the quad-mount Bofors 40 mm while lacking the range and power that the Bofors provided.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The gun was relegated to smaller less vital ships by the end of the war.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The 5"/38 naval gun rounded out the US Navy's AA suite.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] A dual purpose mount, it was used in both the surface and AA roles with great success.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Mated with the Mark 37 director and the proximity fuse it could routinely knock drones out of the sky at ranges as far as 13,000 yards.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] A 3"/50 MK 22 semiautomatic dual gun was produced but not employed before the end of the war and therefore beyond the scope of this article.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] However early marks of the 3"/50 were employed in destroyer escorts and on merchant ships.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] 3″/50 caliber guns (Marks 10, 17, 18, and 20) first entered service in 1915 as a refit to USS *Texas* (BB-35), and were subsequently mounted on many types of ships as the need for anti-aircraft protection was recognised.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] During World War II, they were the primary gun armament on destroyer escorts, patrol frigates, submarine chasers, minesweepers, some fleet submarines, and other auxiliary vessels, and were used as a secondary dual-purpose battery on some other types of ships, including some older battleships.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] They also replaced the original low-angle 4"/50 caliber guns (Mark 9) on "flush-deck" *Wickes* and *Clemson*-class destroyers to provide better anti-aircraft protection.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The gun was also used on specialist destroyer conversions; the "AVD" seaplane tender conversions received two guns; the "APD" high-speed transports, "DM" minelayers, and "DMS" minesweeper conversions received three guns, and those retaining destroyer classification received six.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The Germans developed massive reinforced-concrete blockhouses, some more than six stories high, which were known as *Hochbunker* 'high bunkers' or "*Flaktürme*" flak towers, on which they placed anti-aircraft artillery.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Those in cities attacked by the Allied land forces became fortresses.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Several in Berlin were some of the last buildings to fall to the Soviets during the Battle of Berlin in 1945.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The British built structures such as the Maunsell Forts in the North Sea, the Thames Estuary and other tidal areas upon which they based guns.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Some were outside territorial waters, and had a second life in the 1960s as platforms for pirate radio stations, while another became the base of a micronation, the Principality of Sealand.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Some nations started rocket research before World War II, including for anti-aircraft use.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Further research started during the war.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The first step was unguided missile systems like the British 2-inch RP and 3-inch, which was fired in large numbers from *Z batteries*, and were also fitted to warships.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The firing of one of these devices during an air raid is suspected to have caused the Bethnal Green disaster in 1943.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Facing the threat of Japanese Kamikaze attacks the British and US developed surface-to-air rockets like British Fairey Stooge or the American Lark as counter measures, but none of them were ready at the end of the war.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The Germans missile research was the most advanced of the war as the Germans put considerable effort in the research and development of rocket systems for all purposes.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Among them were several guided and unguided systems.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Unguided systems involved the Fliegerfaust (literally "aircraft fist") rocket launcher as the first MANPADS.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Guided systems were several sophisticated radio, wire, or radar guided missiles like the *Wasserfall* ('waterfall') rocket.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Owing to the severe war situation for Germany all of those systems were only produced in small numbers and most of them were only used by training or trial units.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Another aspect of anti-aircraft defence was the use of barrage balloons to act as physical obstacle initially to bomber aircraft over cities and later for ground attack aircraft over the Normandy invasion fleets.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The balloon, a simple blimp tethered to the ground, worked in two ways.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Firstly, it and the steel cable were a danger to any aircraft that tried to fly among them.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Secondly, to avoid the balloons, bombers had to fly at a higher altitude, which was more favourable for the guns.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Barrage balloons were limited in application, and had minimal success at bringing down aircraft, being largely immobile and passive defences.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The Allies' most advanced technologies were showcased by the anti-aircraft defence against the German V-1 cruise missiles (V stands for *Vergeltungswaffe*, 'retaliation weapon').
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The 419th and 601st anti-aircraft gun battalions of the US Army were first allocated to the Folkestone-Dover coast to defend London, and then moved to Belgium to become part of the "Antwerp X" project coordinated from the Le Grand Veneur in Keerbergen.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] With the liberation of Antwerp, the port city immediately became the highest priority target, and received the largest number of V-1 and V-2 missiles of any city.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The smallest tactical unit of the operation was a gun battery consisting of four 90 mm guns firing shells equipped with a radio proximity fuse.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Incoming targets were acquired and automatically tracked by SCR-584 radar,.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Output from the gun-laying radar was fed to the M9 Gun Director, an electronic analogue computer to calculate the lead and elevation corrections for the guns.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] With the help of these three technologies, close to 90% of the V-1 missiles, on track to the defence zone around the port, were destroyed in a single week in March 1945.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Post-war analysis demonstrated that even with newest anti-aircraft systems employed by both sides, the vast majority of bombers reached their targets successfully, on the order of 90%.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] While these figures were undesirable during the war, the advent of the nuclear bomb considerably altered the acceptability of even a single bomber reaching its target.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The developments during World War II continued for a short time into the post-war period as well.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In particular the US Army set up a huge air defence network around its larger cities based on radar-guided 90 mm and 120 mm guns.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] US efforts continued into the 1950s with the 75 mm Skysweeper system, an almost fully automated system including the radar, computers, power, and auto-loading gun on a single powered platform.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The Skysweeper replaced all smaller guns then in use in the Army, notably the 40 mm Bofors.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] By 1955, the US military deemed the 40 mm Bofors obsolete due to its reduced capability to shoot down jet powered aircraft, and turned to SAM development, with the Nike Ajax and the RSD-58.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In Europe NATO's Allied Command Europe developed an integrated air defence system, NATO Air Defence Ground Environment (NADGE), that later became the NATO Integrated Air Defence System.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The introduction of the guided missile resulted in a significant shift in anti-aircraft strategy.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Although Germany had been desperate to introduce anti-aircraft missile systems, none became operational during World War II.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Following several years of post-war development, however, these systems began to mature into viable weapons.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The US started an upgrade of their defences using the Nike Ajax missile, and soon the larger anti-aircraft guns disappeared.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The same thing occurred in the USSR after the introduction of their SA-2 Guideline systems.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] As this process continued, the missile found itself being used for more and more of the roles formerly filled by guns.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] First to go were the large weapons, replaced by equally large missile systems of much higher performance.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Smaller missiles soon followed, eventually becoming small enough to be mounted on armoured cars and tank chassis.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] These started replacing, or at least supplanting, similar gun-based SPAAG systems in the 1960s, and by the 1990s had replaced almost all such systems in modern armies.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Man-portable missiles, MANPADS, as they are known today, were introduced in the 1960s and have supplanted or replaced even the smallest guns in most advanced armies.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In the 1982 Falklands War, the Argentine armed forces deployed the newest west European weapons including the 35 mm Oerlikon GDF-002 twin cannon and Roland missile.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] The Rapier missile system was the primary GBAD system, used by both British artillery and RAF regiment, a few brand-new FIM-92 Stinger were used by British special forces.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Both sides also used the Blowpipe missile.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] British naval missiles used included Sea Dart and the older Sea Slug longer range systems, SeaCat and the new Sea Wolf short range systems.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] Machine guns in AA mountings were used both ashore and afloat.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] During the 2008 South Ossetia war air power faced off against powerful SAM systems, like the 1980s Buk-M1.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In February 2018, an Israeli F-16 fighter was downed in the Golan Heights province, after it had attacked an Iranian target in Syria.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p02] In 2006, Israel also lost a helicopter over Lebanon, shot down by a Hezbollah rocket.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Although the firearms used by the infantry, particularly machine guns, can be used to engage low altitude air targets, on occasion with notable success, their effectiveness is generally limited and the muzzle flashes reveal infantry positions.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Speed and altitude of modern jet aircraft limit target opportunities, and critical systems may be armoured in aircraft designed for the ground attack role.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] The shells fired by these weapons are usually fitted with different types of fuses (barometric, time-delay, or proximity) to explode close to the airborne target, releasing a shower of fast metal fragments.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] For shorter-range work, a lighter weapon with a higher rate of fire is required, to increase a hit probability on a fast airborne target.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Weapons between 20 mm and 40 mm calibre have been widely used in this role.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Smaller weapons, typically .50 calibre or even 8 mm rifle calibre guns have been used in the smallest mounts.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Unlike the heavier guns, these smaller weapons are in widespread use due to their low cost and ability to quickly follow the target.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Classic examples of autocannons and large calibre guns are the 40 mm autocannon from Bofors and the 8.8 cm FlaK 18, 36 gun designed by Krupp.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Artillery weapons of this sort have for the most part been superseded by the effective surface-to-air missile systems that were introduced in the 1950s, although they were still retained by many nations.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Land-based SAMs can be deployed from fixed installations or mobile launchers, either wheeled or tracked.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] The tracked vehicles are usually armoured vehicles specifically designed to carry SAMs.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Larger SAMs may be deployed in fixed launchers, but can be towed/re-deployed at will.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] The SAMs launched by individuals are known in the United States as the Man-Portable Air Defence Systems (MANPADS).
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] MANPADS of the former Soviet Union have been exported around the World, and can be found in use by many armed forces.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Targets for non-ManPAD SAMs will usually be acquired by air-search radar, then tracked before/while a SAM is "locked-on" and then fired.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Potential targets, if they are military aircraft, will be identified as friend or foe before being engaged.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] The developments in the latest and relatively cheap short-range missiles have begun to replace autocannons in this role.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] The interceptor aircraft (or simply interceptor) is a type of fighter aircraft designed specifically to intercept and destroy enemy aircraft, particularly bombers, usually relying on high speed and altitude capabilities.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] A number of jet interceptors such as the F-102 Delta Dagger, the F-106 Delta Dart, and the MiG-25 were built in the period starting after the end of World War II and ending in the late 1960s, when they became less important due to the shifting of the strategic bombing role to ICBMs.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Invariably the type is differentiated from other fighter aircraft designs by higher speeds and shorter operating ranges, as well as much reduced ordnance payloads.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] The radar systems use electromagnetic waves to identify the range, altitude, direction, or speed of aircraft and weather formations to provide tactical and operational warning and direction, primarily during defensive operations.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] In their functional roles they provide target search, threat detection, guidance, reconnaissance, navigation, instrumentation, and weather reporting support to combat operations.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] An *anti-UAV defence system* (AUDS) is a system for defence against military unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] A variety of designs have been developed, using lasers, net-guns and air-to-air netting, signal jamming, and hi-jacking by means of in-flight hacking.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Anti-UAV defence systems have been deployed against ISIL drones during the Battle of Mosul (2016–2017).
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Alternative approaches for dealing with UAVs have included using a shotgun at close range, and for smaller drones, training eagles to snatch them from the air.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] This only works on relatively small UAVs and loitering munitions (also called "suicide drones").
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Larger UCAVs such as the MQ-1 Predator can be (and frequently are) shot down like manned aircraft of similar sizes and flight profiles.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] The US Navy began its railgun project in 2005, with tests in December 2010 achieving a world record muzzle energy of 33 MJ (24×10^6 ft⋅lbf), launching a 10.4 kg (23 lb) projectile at 2.5 km/s (8,200 ft/s).
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] This gun was planned to fire up to 10 times a minute, with self-guided projectiles hitting 5 m (16 ft) targets at 200 nautical miles (370 km) when ready, projected to be between 2020 and 2025.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] However, funding was pulled from the program in mid-2021, though the projectile's development was continued for use in conventional guns.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] The Japanese Maritime Self-Defense Force conducting the first known successful test firing of a railgun at sea in October 2023, with the 40 mm (1.6 in) gun firing 320-gram (0.71 lb) projectiles at over 2,000 metres per second (4,500 mph).
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] The railgun is mounted in a turret aboard the experimental ship JS Asuka, and is designed to be used against surface targets as well as hypersonic missiles.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Upsetting this development to all-missile systems is the current move to stealth aircraft.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Long range missiles depend on long-range detection to provide significant lead.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Stealth designs cut detection ranges so much that the aircraft is often never even seen, and when it is, it is often too late for an intercept.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Systems for detection and tracking of stealthy aircraft are a major problem for anti-aircraft development.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] However, as stealth technology grows, so does anti-stealth technology.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Multiple transmitter radars such as those from bistatic radars and low-frequency radars are said to have the capabilities to detect stealth aircraft.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Advanced forms of thermographic cameras such as those that incorporate QWIPs would be able to optically see a stealth aircraft regardless of the aircraft's radar cross-section (RCS).
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] In addition, side-looking radars, high-powered optical satellites, and sky-scanning, high-aperture, high sensitivity radars such as radio telescopes, would all be able to narrow down the location of a stealth aircraft under certain parameters.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] The newest SAMs have a claimed ability to be able to detect and engage stealth targets, with the most notable being the Russian S-400, which is claimed to be able to detect a target with a 0.05-square metre RCS from 90 km away.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Another potential weapon system for anti-aircraft use is the laser.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Although air planners have imagined lasers in combat since the late 1960s, only the most modern laser systems are currently reaching what could be considered "experimental usefulness".
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] In particular the Tactical High Energy Laser can be used in the anti-aircraft and anti-missile role.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Most Western and Commonwealth militaries integrate air defence purely with the traditional services of the military (i.e. army, navy and air force), as a separate arm or as part of artillery.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] In the British Army for instance, air defence is part of the artillery arm, while in the Pakistan Army, it was split off from the artillery to form a separate arm of its own in 1990.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] This is in contrast to some (largely communist or ex-communist) countries where not only are there provisions for air defence in the army, navy and air force but there are specific branches that deal only with the air defence of territory, for example, the Soviet PVO Strany.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] The USSR also had a separate strategic rocket force in charge of nuclear intercontinental ballistic missiles.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Smaller boats and ships typically have machine-guns or fast cannons, which can often be deadly to low-flying aircraft if linked to a radar-directed fire-control system radar-controlled cannon for point defence.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Some vessels like Aegis-equipped destroyers and cruisers are as much a threat to aircraft as any land-based air defence system.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] In general, naval vessels should be treated with respect by aircraft, however the reverse is equally true.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Carrier battle groups are especially well defended, as not only do they typically consist of many vessels with heavy air defence armament but they are also able to launch fighter jets for combat air patrol overhead to intercept incoming airborne threats.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Some modern submarines, such as the Type 212 submarines of the German Navy, are equipped with surface-to-air missile systems, since helicopters and anti-submarine warfare aircraft are significant threats.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] The subsurface launched anti-air missile was first purposed by US Navy Rear Admiral Charles B.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Layered air defence in naval tactics, especially within a carrier group, is often built around a system of concentric layers with the aircraft carrier at the centre.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] The outer layer will usually be provided by the carrier's aircraft, specifically its AEW&C aircraft combined with the CAP.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Finally, virtually every modern warship will be fitted with small-calibre guns, including a CIWS, which is usually a radar-controlled Gatling gun of between 20 mm and 30 mm calibre capable of firing several thousand rounds per minute.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Armies typically have air defence in depth, from integral man-portable air-defence systems (MANPADS) such as the RBS 70, Stinger and Igla at smaller force levels up to army-level missile defence systems such as Angara and Patriot.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Often, the high-altitude long-range missile systems force aircraft to fly at low level, where anti-aircraft guns can bring them down.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] As well as the small and large systems, for effective air defence there must be intermediate systems.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] These may be deployed at regiment-level and consist of platoons of self-propelled anti-aircraft platforms, whether they are self-propelled anti-aircraft guns (SPAAGs), integrated air-defence systems like 2K22 Tunguska or all-in-one surface-to-air missile platforms like Roland or SA-8 Gecko.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] On a national level the United States Army was atypical in that it was primarily responsible for the missile air defences of the Continental United States with systems such as Project Nike.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Air defence by air forces is typically provided by fighter jets carrying air-to-air missiles.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] However, most air forces choose to augment airbase defence with surface-to-air missile systems as they are such valuable targets and subject to attack by enemy aircraft.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] In addition, some countries choose to put all air defence responsibilities under the air force.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Area air defence, the air defence of a specific area or location, (as opposed to point defence), have historically been operated by both armies (Anti-Aircraft Command in the British Army, for instance) and Air Forces (the United States Air Force's CIM-10 Bomarc).
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Area defence systems have medium to long range and can be made up of various other systems and networked into an area defence system (in which case it may be made up of several short range systems combined to effectively cover an area).
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] An example of area defence is the defence of Saudi Arabia and Israel by MIM-104 Patriot missile batteries during the first Gulf War, where the objective was to cover populated areas.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Most modern air defence systems are fairly mobile.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Even the larger systems tend to be mounted on trailers and are designed to be fairly quickly broken down or set up.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] In the past, this was not always the case.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Early missile systems were cumbersome and required much infrastructure; many could not be moved at all.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] With the diversification of air defence there has been much more emphasis on mobility.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Most modern systems are usually either self-propelled (i.e. guns or missiles are mounted on a truck or tracked chassis) or towed.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Even systems that consist of many components (transporter/erector/launchers, radars, command posts etc.) benefit from being mounted on a fleet of vehicles.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] In general, a fixed system can be identified, attacked and destroyed whereas a mobile system can show up in places where it is not expected.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Soviet systems especially concentrate on mobility, after the lessons learnt in the Vietnam War between the US and Vietnam with the SA-2 Guideline.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Many nations have developed significant tactics for air defence suppression.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Dedicated weapons such as anti-radiation missiles and advanced electronics intelligence and electronic countermeasures platforms seek to suppress or negate the effectiveness of an opposing air-defence system.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] It is an arms race; as better jamming, countermeasures and anti-radiation weapons are developed, so are better SAM systems with ECCM capabilities and the ability to shoot down anti-radiation missiles and other munitions aimed at them or the targets they are defending.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Stinger missiles supplied by the United States were used against the aircraft of the Soviet Union by the Afghan *mujahideen* during the Soviet occupation of Afghanistan in the Cold War.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Rocket-propelled grenades (RPGs) can be—and often are—used against hovering helicopters (e.g., by Somali militiamen during the 1993 Battle of Mogadishu.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Firing an RPG at steep angles poses a danger to the user, because the backblast from firing reflects off the ground.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] In Somalia, militia members sometimes welded a steel plate onto the exhaust end of an RPG's tube to deflect pressure away from the shooter when shooting up at US helicopters.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] RPGs are used in this role only when more effective weapons are not available.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Another example of using RPGs against helicopters is Operation Anaconda in March 2002 in Afghanistan.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Taliban insurgents defending Shah-i-Kot Valley used RPGs in a direct fire role against landing helicopters.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Four rangers were killed when their helicopter was shot down by an RPG, and SEAL team member Neil C.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] Roberts fell out of his helicopter when it was hit by two RPGs.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] In other instances helicopters have been shot down in Afghanistan during a mission in Wardak province.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] One feature that makes RPGs useful in air defence is that they are fused to automatically detonate at 920 m.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] If aimed into the air this causes the warhead to airburst which can release a limited but potentially damaging amount of shrapnel hitting a helicopter landing or taking off.
[src:conning-tower/aa-gun-p03] A recent trend emerging during the Syrian Civil War is the use of ATGM against landing helicopters.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The **Admiral-class battlecruisers** were to have been a class of four British Royal Navy battlecruisers built near the end of World War I.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The class was to have consisted of HMS *Hood*, *Anson*, *Howe*, and *Rodney* — all names of famous admirals — but the latter three ships were suspended as the material and labour required to complete them was needed for higher-priority merchantmen and escort vessels.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Their designs were updated to incorporate the lessons from the Battle of Jutland, but the Admiralty eventually decided that it was better to begin again with a clean-slate design so they were cancelled in 1919.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] No more battlecruisers would be built due to the arms limitations agreements of the interbellum.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] In 1915 the Admiralty was considering the next generation of warship to follow the *Queen Elizabeth*-class battleships.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The Director of Naval Construction (DNC), Sir Eustace Tennyson-d'Eyncourt, was given instructions to prepare designs for a new battleship.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The DNC had been able to reduce the draught in comparison to *Queen Elizabeth* by 22% by widening the ship to 104 feet (31.7 m) and lengthening it to 810 feet (246.9 m); this had the consequence of restricting the ships to use only one dock in Rosyth and two in Portsmouth.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Large anti-torpedo bulges were fitted, and the secondary armament of twelve 5-inch (127 mm) guns of a new design was mounted on the forecastle deck.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The resulting high freeboard gave the design a greater ratio of reserve buoyancy to displacement than in any previous British dreadnought.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The design's stretched hull form also gave her an estimated speed of 26.5 knots (49.1 km/h; 30.5 mph), about 2.5 knots (4.6 km/h; 2.9 mph) faster than *Queen Elizabeth* had been able to reach in service.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The First Sea Lord, Admiral Sir Henry Jackson, responded on 6 December that such a large ship might start a new arms race with the Americans that Britain could ill afford, and that better deck protection was necessary to defeat plunging shells during long-range engagements.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The Admiralty asked for the design to be reworked ('B') with a maximum beam of 90 feet (27.4 m), but this was deemed unsatisfactory as it compromised the ship's underwater protection.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] A pair of revised designs was requested with the speed reduced to 22 knots (41 km/h; 25 mph) to allow the hull to be shortened to better fit in existing floating docks and the minimum possible draught.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The first of the two ('C1') was to have full bulge protection and the second ('C2') to have the best bulge protection possible without exceeding *Queen Elizabeth*'s length.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] 'C1' was shortened by 100 feet (30.5 m) in comparison with 'B' and 'C2' was only 610 feet (185.9 m) in length, but draught increased by 1 foot 3 inches (0.38 m).
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] In both proposals it had been necessary to reduce the number of guns in the secondary armament and reduce the thickness of the armour.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The Admiralty was not pleased with either design and asked for a revised version of 'A' of the same draught, beam, armour and armament, but shortened and with the same speed as *Queen Elizabeth*.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] In addition the new five-inch gun was rejected in favour of the existing 5.5-inch (140 mm) gun.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] At least some of the designs were passed to Admiral John Jellicoe, commander of the Grand Fleet, who pointed out that there was no need for new battleships as the British superiority in numbers over the Germans was substantial, but that was not true for battlecruisers.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Germany was known to be building three new *Mackensen*-class battlecruisers with an estimated speed approaching 30 knots (56 km/h; 35 mph) and a reported armament of 15.2-inch (386 mm) guns.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] These ships would be superior to all existing British battlecruisers, and those then under construction (the two *Renown*-class and the three *Courageous*-class 'large light cruisers') were equally fast, but too thinly armoured to compete with them.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The DNC prepared two new designs in response to Admiral Jellicoe's comments on 1 February 1916, each for a battlecruiser capable of thirty knots or better and armed with eight 15-inch (381 mm) guns.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Design '1' displaced 39,000 long tons (39,626 t) with two inches less belt armour and a speed of thirty knots.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] It used the bulky large-tube boilers traditional in British capital ships, which explains why the design was 9,000 long tons (9,144 t) larger than any of the previous battleship designs.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Design '2' was essentially a repeat of the first design except that small-tube boilers were substituted.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] These were considerably smaller than the older type and saved 3,500 long tons (3,556 t) over Design '1' and had one foot less draught.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] These savings were substantial enough to overcome the Engineer-in-Chief's objections that they required more frequent and expensive repairs.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The DNC was asked to submit four more designs using small-tube boilers which were submitted on 17 February.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Design '3' was Design '2' with the machinery power increased to 160,000 shaft horsepower (120,000 kW) to boost the maximum speed to 32 knots (59 km/h; 37 mph) while the other designs had either four, six or eight 18-inch (457 mm) guns.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Design '3' was selected as Admiral Jellicoe had specified that the minimum number of guns should be no less than eight as fewer caused problems in accurate fire control, and two alternatives were to be provided, one with a dozen 5.5-inch guns and the other with sixteen such guns.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The latter proposal was selected on 7 April and orders were placed on 19 April for three ships (*Hood*, *Howe* and *Rodney*).
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The order for the fourth ship, *Anson*, was placed on 13 June.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] On 5 July the DNC submitted two revised designs for the Admiral-class ships.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The first was a modification of the previous design with slight increases to the deck, turret, barbette, and funnel uptake armour, one-inch protection for the 5.5-inch ammunition hatches and hoists, and the number of electrical generators increased from four to eight.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] These changes increased the displacement by 1,250 long tons (1,270 t) and draught by 9 inches (228.6 mm).
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The second design drastically improved the protection and converted the ships into fast battleships.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The vertical armour was generally increased by 50% and the deck protection was slightly thickened as in the first design.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] These changes would have added another 4,300 long tons (4,369 t) to the original design and increased the draught by 2 feet (0.6 m), but would have cost half a knot in speed.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] This design would have been equal to the *Queen Elizabeth*s, but 7 knots (13 km/h; 8.1 mph) faster and with much improved torpedo protection, although it was some 13,000 long tons (13,209 t) larger than the older ships.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] After the DNC submitted the above designs, he was asked to consider variations with triple fifteen-inch turrets, and these were submitted on 20 July.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The Admiralty chose the fast battleship design, and *Hood* was laid down again on 1 September.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Further alterations were made in 1917 during her construction that increased the thickness of her turret faces and roofs.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] These changes, plus numerous others, increased her displacement by 600 long tons (610 t) and her draught by 3 inches (76.2 mm), and reduced her speed to 31 knots (57 km/h; 36 mph).
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The changes continued during 1918 when the thickness of her magazine crowns was increased from one inch to two; the armour for the funnel uptakes above the forecastle deck was omitted in compensation.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] In May 1919 her main deck armour at the side abreast the magazines was increased to three inches (76 mm), and four 5.5-inch guns and their ammunition were deleted in consequence.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] However, the additional deck armour was never fitted and the torpedo tubes (less their protection) were retained.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Design work continued however, although *Hood* was too far advanced to incorporate these changes, and ultimately would have been extensive enough for the other three ships to constitute their own class.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] At the end of 1917 the suspended ships' design was modified to increase the thickness of the turret roofs to six inches (152 mm), and (unspecified) alterations were made to the armoured bulkheads.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] These cost a total of 267 long tons (271 t) in displacement.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Other changes were a redesigned bridge structure and moving the funnels closer together and the exchange in position between the fifteen-inch shellrooms and magazines.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] This latter change would have caused the hull's form to be filled out somewhat to accommodate the handling room of the rearmost turret at the cost of a slight loss in speed and ammunition storage.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The Admiral-class ships were significantly larger than their predecessors of the *Renown* class.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] They had an overall length of 860 feet (262.1 m), a beam of 104 feet (31.7 m), and a draught of 31 feet 6 inches (9.6 m) at deep load.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] This was 64 feet (19.5 m) longer and 14 feet (4.3 m) wider than the smaller ships.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] They had a metacentric height of 4.6 feet (1.4 m) at deep load as well as a complete double bottom.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The ships had four Brown-Curtis single-reduction geared steam turbine sets, each of which drove one propeller shaft.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] They were arranged in three engine rooms.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The forward engine room held the two turbines for the wing shafts, the middle compartment housed the turbines for the port inner shaft and the aft engine room contained the turbines for the starboard inner shaft.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] A cruising turbine was built into the casing of each wing turbine.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The turbines were powered by twenty-four Yarrow small-tube boilers equally divided between four boiler rooms.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] They were designed to produce a total of 144,000 shaft horsepower (107,000 kW) at a working pressure of 235 psi (1,620 kPa), but achieved more than 151,000 shp (112,601 kW) during *Hood*'s trials, when she slightly exceeded her designed speed of 31 knots (57 km/h; 36 mph).
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] They were designed to normally carry 1,200 long tons (1,219 t) of fuel oil, but had a maximum capacity of 4,000 long tons (4,064 t).
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] At full capacity, *Hood* could steam at a speed of 14 knots (26 km/h; 16 mph) for an estimated 7,500 nautical miles (13,890 km; 8,630 mi).
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] They had eight 175-kilowatt (235 hp) dynamos, two diesel, two turbo-driven, and four reciprocating.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The Admiral-class ships mounted eight BL 15-inch Mk I guns in four twin hydraulically powered Mark II turrets, designated 'A', 'B', 'X' and 'Y' from front to rear.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The guns could be depressed to −3° and elevated to 30°; they could be loaded at any angle up to 20°, although loading at high angles tended to slow the gun's return to battery.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] They fired 1,920-pound (871 kg) projectiles at a muzzle velocity of 2,467 ft/s (752 m/s); this provided a maximum range of 29,000 yd (26,518 m) with armour-piercing (AP) shells.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Their secondary armament consisted of sixteen BL 5.5-inch Mk I guns, which were mounted on pivot mounts on the forecastle deck, protected by gun shields.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] They were provided with 200 rounds per gun.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The guns on their CPII mounts had a maximum elevation of 30°.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] They fired 82-pound (37 kg) projectiles at a muzzle velocity of 2,790 ft/s (850 m/s).
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Their rate of fire was twelve rounds per minute.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The Admiral-class ships were designed with four QF four-inch Mark V anti-aircraft guns.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] They had a maximum depression of -5° and a maximum elevation of 80°.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] They fired a 31-pound (14 kg) high explosive shell at a muzzle velocity of 2,387 ft/s (728 m/s) at a rate of ten to fifteen rounds per minute.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The guns had a maximum ceiling of 31,000 ft (9,400 m), but an effective range of much less.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Two 21-inch (533 mm) submerged side-loading torpedo tubes were fitted forward of 'A' turret and eight above-water side-loading Mark V tubes were intended to be mounted abreast the rear funnel on the upper deck, although only four of the latter were carried by *Hood*.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] They were loaded and traversed by hydraulic power; the submerged tubes were fired by compressed air while the above-water tubes used cordite charges.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Thirty-two warheads could be accommodated in the two magazines in the hold forward of 'A' turret's shellroom.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] *Hood* carried Mark IV and IV* torpedoes, each which had a warhead of 515 pounds (234 kg) of TNT.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The main guns of the Admiral-class ships were controlled from either of the two fire-control directors.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The primary director was mounted above the conning tower in an armoured hood and the other was in the fore-top on the foremast.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] 'B' turret could also control all the main gun turrets while 'X' turret could control the rear guns.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Data from a 30-foot (9.1 m) rangefinder in the armoured hood were input into a Mk V Dreyer Fire Control Table located in the Transmitting Station (TS) on the platform deck where they were converted into range and deflection data for use by the guns.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The target's data were also graphically recorded on a plotting table to assist the gunnery officer in predicting the movement of the target.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The fore-top was equipped with a 15-foot (4.6 m) rangefinder.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Each turret was provided with a thirty-foot rangefinder in an armoured housing on the turret roof and a Dumaresq analogue computer for local fire-control.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The secondary armament was primarily controlled by the 5.5-inch directors mounted on each side of the bridge.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] They were supplemented by the two additional control positions in the fore-top, which were provided with 9-foot (2.7 m) rangefinders.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The anti-aircraft guns were controlled by a simple 2-metre (6 ft 7 in) rangefinder mounted on the aft superstructure.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The torpedoes initially had a similar system where various rangefinders, especially the fifteen-foot rangefinder above the aft torpedo control tower, and deflection sights provided data to a Dreyer table in the torpedo TS adjacent to the 5.5-inch TS on the lower deck.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] However the Dreyer table was removed during *Hood*'s 1929–1931 refit and the calculations were made in the torpedo control position in the bridge.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The waterline belt of the Admiral-class ships was 12 inches (305 mm) thick, angled 12° outwards partly to keep the belt inside the bulge structure and allow torpedo hits to vent to the atmosphere.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] This angle also increased the armour's relative thickness to horizontal, close-range fire, albeit at the cost of reducing its relative height which increased the chance of plunging shellfire going over or under it.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] This sloped belt made their armour comparable to the 13 inches (330 mm) found in the latest British dreadnoughts.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] It ran some 562 feet (171.3 m), from the forward edge of 'A' barbette to the middle of 'Y' barbette.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Forward of this the belt thinned to six inches before further reducing to 5 inches (127 mm) and ending in a five-inch (127 mm) bulkhead well short of the bow.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Aft of the midships section the belt reduced to six inches (152 mm); it did not reach the stern, but terminated at a five-inch bulkhead.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] This belt had a height of 9 feet 6 inches (2.9 m), which 4 feet (1.2 m) was below the designed waterline.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Above it was the seven-inch middle belt, 7 feet (2.1 m) high, and the five-inch upper belt, which was 9 feet (2.7 m) high.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The middle belt stretched between 'A' and 'Y' barbettes, ending in four-inch transverse bulkheads at each end.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The upper belt only ran from 'A' barbette to the end of the machinery spaces and ended in another four-inch transverse bulkhead.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Five of *Hood*'s decks were armoured with thicknesses varying from .75 to 3 inches (19 to 76 mm), with the greatest thicknesses over the magazines and the steering gear.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Immediately adjacent to 'A' and 'Y' barbettes the main deck was five inches thick to protect the magazines.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The turret faces were fifteen inches thick while their sides ranged from 11 to 12 inches (279 to 305 mm) in thickness, and the roof was five inches thick.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The barbettes had a maximum of twelve inches of armour, but were reduced in thickness in stages below decks, although the outer faces of 'A' and 'Y' barbettes were considerably thicker below decks than the other barbettes.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The conning tower armour was nine to eleven inches thick, and it was the largest yet fitted to a British capital ship as it weighed 600 long tons (610 t).
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The primary fire-control director atop the conning tower was protected by an armoured hood.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The face of the hood was six inches thick, its sides were two inches thick, and its roof was protected by three inches of armour.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] A communications tube with six-inch sides ran from the conning tower down to the lower conning position on the main deck.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The three torpedo bulkheads were 1.5 inches (38 mm), 1 inch (25 mm) and .75 inches (19 mm) thick.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The anti-torpedo bulges of the Admiral-class battlecruisers were the first fitted on a British capital ship to fully incorporate the lessons learned from a series of experiments begun before World War I.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] They consisted of an outer air space, an inner buoyancy space and the 1.5-inch protective bulkhead.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The buoyancy space was filled with sealed steel crushing tubes intended to distribute the force of an explosion over as wide an area as possible as well as absorb as much of its force as possible.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] However, tests conducted after *Hood* was completed showed that filling the buoyancy space with water was equally effective and considerably cheaper.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Shortly after commissioning on 15 May 1920 *Hood* became flagship of the Battlecruiser Squadron of the Atlantic Fleet, under the command of Rear Admiral Sir Roger Keyes.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] She made a cruise to Scandinavian waters that year.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] She visited the Mediterranean in 1921 and 1922 to show the flag and to train with the Mediterranean Fleet, before sailing on a cruise to Brazil and the West Indies in company with the Battlecruiser Squadron.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] In November 1923 *Hood*, accompanied by the battlecruiser *Repulse* and a number of *Danae*-class cruisers of the 1st Light Cruiser Squadron, set out on a world cruise from west to east via the Panama Canal.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] They returned home ten months later in September 1924.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The Battlecruiser Squadron visited Lisbon in January 1925 to participate in the Vasco da Gama celebrations before continuing on the Mediterranean for exercises.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] *Hood* would continue this pattern of a winter training visit to the Mediterranean for the rest of the decade.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] In September 1939, she was hit by a 250 kg (550 lb) aircraft bomb with minor damage.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] By early 1940 *Hood*'s machinery was in dire shape and limited her best speed to 26.5 knots (49.1 km/h; 30.5 mph); she was refitted between 4 April and 12 June.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] They had not yet reached the Strait when *Suffolk* spotted the German ships north of Iceland in the early evening on 23 May.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] *Hood* and *Prince of Wales* altered course and increased their speed to intercept.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The British squadron spotted the Germans at 05:37 but the Germans were already aware of their presence.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The British opened fire at 05:52 with *Hood* engaging *Prinz Eugen*, the lead ship in the German formation, and the Germans returned fire 05:55, both ships concentrating on *Hood*.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] *Prinz Eugen* (probably) was the first ship to score when a shell hit *Hood*'s boat deck, between her funnels, and started a large fire among the ready-use ammunition for the anti-aircraft guns and rockets of the Unrotated Projectile mounts.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] Right before 06:00, while *Hood* was turning 20° to port to unmask her rear turrets, she was hit again on the boat deck by a shell from *Bismarck*'s fifth salvo.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] The exact location and sequence of events is unknown, but her aft fifteen-inch magazines exploded.
[src:conning-tower/admiral-class-battlecruiser] This broke her back and she sank with the loss of all but three of her crew.
[src:conning-tower/andrew-lambert] He served as Honorary Secretary of the Navy Records Society from 1996 until 2005 and is a Fellow of the Royal Historical Society.
[src:conning-tower/andrew-lambert] Lambert's work focuses on the naval and strategic history of the British Empire between the Napoleonic Wars and the First World War, and the early development of naval historical writing.
[src:conning-tower/andrew-lambert] His work has addressed a range of issues, including technology, policy-making, regional security, deterrence, historiography, crisis-management and conflict.
[src:conning-tower/andrew-lambert] He has lectured on aspects of his work in Australia, Canada, Finland, Denmark and Russia.
[src:conning-tower/andrew-lambert] In addition, he wrote and presented for the BBC the television series *War at Sea* in 2004.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The **armored cruiser** was a type of warship of the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] It was designed like other types of cruisers to operate as a long-range, independent warship, capable of defeating any ship apart from a pre-dreadnought battleship and fast enough to outrun any battleship it encountered.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] For many decades, naval technology had not advanced far enough for designers to produce a cruiser that combined an armored belt with the long-range and high speed required to fulfill its mission.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] For this reason, beginning in the 1880s and 1890s, many navies preferred to build protected cruisers, which only relied on a lightly armored deck to protect the vital parts of the ship.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] However, by the late 1880s, the development of modern rapid-fire breech-loading cannons and high-explosive shells made the reintroduction of side armor a necessity.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The invention of case-hardened armor in the mid-1890s offered effective protection with less weight than previously.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Varying in size, the armored cruiser was distinguished from other types of cruiser by its belt armor—thick iron (or later steel) plating on much of the hull to protect the ship from shellfire much like that on battleships.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The first armored cruiser, the Imperial Russian Navy's *General-Admiral*, was launched in 1873 and combined sail and steam propulsion.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] By the 1890s, cruisers had abandoned sail and took on a modern appearance.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] In 1908, the armored cruiser was supplanted by the battlecruiser, which, with armament equivalent to that of a dreadnought battleship and speed equivalent to that of a cruiser, was faster and more powerful than an armored cruiser.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] At around the same time there was a successor to the protected cruiser, the "light cruiser" which described small cruisers with armored belts.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Although they were now considered second-rate ships, armored cruisers were still widely used in World War I due to their speed and range, and being able to outgun all but battlecruisers and battleships (both pre-dreadnought and dreadnought types).
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] A handful survived in one form or another until World War II.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Only one, the Greek Navy's *Georgios Averof*, has survived to the modern day as a museum ship.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The armored cruiser was developed in the 1870s as an attempt to combine the virtues of the armored ironclad warship and the fast and long-ranged, but unarmored, cruisers of the time.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Such a ship was desirable to protect overseas trade and, especially for the French and British, to police their vast overseas empires.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The concern within higher naval circles was that without ships that could fulfill these requirements and incorporate new technology, their fleet would become obsolete and ineffective should a war at sea arise.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Concern over obsolescence in official circles was further fueled by the race between the increasing size of naval guns and of armor strong enough to withstand such fire.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] In 1860, one of the largest naval cannons in standard use had a bore of 8 inches (203 mm) and fired a 68-pound (31 kg) solid shot or approximately 51-pound (23 kg) spherical shell.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] By 1884, guns with as wide a bore as 16.25 inches (413 mm), firing an 1,800-pound (816 kg) exploding shell, were being mounted on naval vessels.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] This gun could penetrate up to 34 inches of wrought iron, the earliest form of naval armor.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] These were muzzle-loading guns, as had been used on ships from the 1500s.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Breech-loading cannon, which were readopted into naval use in the 1870s, were more destructive than muzzle loaders due to their higher rate of fire.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The development of rifled cannon, which improved accuracy, and advancements in shells were other factors.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Although a cruiser would not likely face the largest-caliber guns of a battleship and many navies commonly used smaller weapons as they did not wear out as fast as larger ones did, cruisers still needed some form of protection to preclude being shot to pieces.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The adoption of rolled iron armor in 1865 and sandwich armor in 1870 gave ships a chance to withstand fire from larger guns.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Both these protective schemes used wood as an important component, which made them extremely heavy and limited speed, the key factor in a cruiser's ability to perform its duties satisfactorily.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Powered by both sail and steam but without the additional weight of armor, these ships could reach speeds of up to 16 or 17 knots.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The most powerful among them were the British *Inconstant*, the U.S.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Navy's *Wampanoag* and the French *Duquesne*.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The British especially had hoped to rely on these vessels to serve the more distant reaches of its empire.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] In the aftermath of the Battle of Hampton Roads in 1862, where United States wooden warships were defeated by the Confederate ironclad CSS *Virginia*, the Admiralty realized that its ships could theoretically encounter an ironclad in any theater of operation.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Ship propulsion was improving but was also taking time to develop.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Naval engines in the 1860s were single-expansion types, in which steam was expanded into a cylinder, pushed a piston and was released.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Compounding, where steam is passed through a series of cylinders of increasing size before being released, was a more efficient process; it allowed the steam to generate more energy and use less coal to go the same distance.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] With greater efficiency came increasingly complex machinery and the larger potential for breakdown.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] However, advances in metallurgy and engineering, the potential for smaller bunkerage and the successful use of compounding in commercial engines made it an attractive option for naval engines, as well.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] By the 1870s, compound engines had become standard for warships.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Compounding by itself did not increase power or speed significantly, although it allowed for a much greater operating range.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Forced-draught systems would help increase power and speed but would not come into use until the early 1890s.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The Russian navy became the first to produce an armored warship intended for commerce raiding, with *General-Admiral*, begun in 1870 and launched in 1873, often referred to as the first armored cruiser.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Armed with six 8-inch (203 mm) and two 6-inch (152 mm) guns, she and her sister *Gerzog Edinburgski* were not fully armored but protected only by a narrow belt along the waterline.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] This belt, moreover, was so heavy that it sat below the ships' waterlines, which limited its benefit still further.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Since they were iron-hulled, however, they were more durable than their wooden counterparts.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] With a top speed of only 12.3 knots (22.8 km/h) and a high coal consumption, which necessitated a full sailing rig, they were not really suited for the role of cruiser.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Nevertheless, these ships were considered a new threat to British commerce in the event of war, the rationale being that any vessel, regardless of its speed, could technically be a threat to overseas commerce.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The British responded with *Shannon*, begun in 1873, launched in 1875 and armed with two 10-inch (254 mm) and seven 9-inch (229 mm) rifled guns.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Two ships of the *Nelson* class followed, armed with four 10-inch and eight 9-inch guns.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] These early armored cruisers were essentially scaled-down versions of the first-rate ironclad warships of the time and, like their Russian counterparts, were essentially belted cruisers.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Their 9-inch belts were thicker than that of the Russians but did not extend the full length of the hull due to weight but tapered off at both ends.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Past this belt, the designers placed a 3-inch (76 mm) armored deck, situated deepest in the ships, to guard magazines and machinery against plunging fire.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Above this deck, space was allocated for coal bunkers and storerooms.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The bunkers served as added protection, since two feet of coal was considered the equivalent of one foot of steel.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Also, if either of the ships became flooded from battle damage, it was hoped the contents of the bunkers and storerooms would aid in their continued buoyancy.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Because of this unarmored protection, these ships could be considered the first protected cruisers.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] However, these ships also shared the liabilities of the Russian ones and because of this, the British Navy was never happy with them.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] *Shannon*'s top speed of 12.25 knots (22.69 km/h) and *Nelson*'s of 14 knots (26 km/h) made them too slow to deal with fast cruisers and they were not armored well enough to take on a first-class battleship.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Their armor belts also sat below the ships' waterlines, which made them of limited benefit.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The underlying problem with these early warships was that technology had not caught up to the demands being made of them; therefore, they represented a series of compromises and could not be fully effective.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] They were typically powered by double-expansion steam engines fed by boilers which generated steam at perhaps 60 or 70 psi pressure, which gave relatively poor efficiency and short range.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Even with improved engines, the dearth of overseas refueling stations made a full sailing rig a necessity.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] (The loss of HMS *Captain* in 1870 with nearly all of her 500-man crew illustrated graphically what could happen in a heavy sea with a steam-and-sail turret ship.) Consequently, armored cruisers retained a more traditional broadside arrangement.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Their armor was distributed in a thick belt around the waterline along most of their length; the gun positions on deck were not necessarily armored at all.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The limitations of these ships would not be rectified fully until decades after their construction.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Meanwhile, a battle in May 1877 between the British unarmored cruiser *Shah* and the Peruvian monitor *Huáscar* demonstrated the need for more and better-protected cruisers.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] *Shah* and the smaller wooden corvette *Amethyst* hit *Huáscar* more than 50 times without causing significant damage.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The Peruvian ship had an inexperienced crew unused to its cumbersome machinery, and managed to fire only six rounds, all of which missed.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The engagement demonstrated the value of cruisers with armor protection.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] During the 1870s, the rapid increase in the size and power of armor-piercing guns caused problems for the designers of battleships and cruisers alike.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Even a ship designed with adequate armor protection from the current generation of guns might be vulnerable to new guns powerful enough to penetrate its armor.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Consequently, naval designers tried a novel method of armoring their ships.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The vital parts—engines, boilers, magazines and enough hull structure to keep the ship stable in the event of damage—could be positioned underneath an armored deck just below the waterline.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] This deck, which would only be struck very obliquely by shells, could be thinner and lighter than belt armor.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The sides of the ship would be entirely unarmored but would be as effective as an armored belt which would not stop shellfire.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Cruisers designed along these guidelines, known as protected cruisers, superseded armored cruisers in the 1880s and early 1890s.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] As mentioned earlier, the armored cruiser *Shannon* was the first ship to make use of an armored deck.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] However, by the end of the 1870s, ships could be found with full–length armored decks and little or no side armor.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The Italian *Italia* class of very fast battleships had armored decks and guns but no side armor.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The British used a full-length armored deck in their *Comus* class of corvettes started in 1878; however the *Comus* class were designed for colonial service and were only capable of 13 knots (24 km/h) speed, not fast enough for commerce protection or fleet duties.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The breakthrough for the protected cruiser design came with the Chilean *Esmeralda*, designed and built by the British firm Armstrong at their Elswick yard.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] *Esmeralda*, with a high speed of 18 knots (33 km/h), dispensed entirely with sails and carried an armament of two 10-inch and six 6-inch guns, considered very powerful for a ship her size.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Her protection scheme, inspired by the *Italia* class, included a full–length protected deck up to 2 inches (51 mm) thick, and a cork-filled cofferdam along her sides.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] *Esmeralda* set the tone for cruiser construction for the years to come, with "Elswick cruisers" on a similar design being constructed for Italy, China, Japan, Argentina, Austria and the United States.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Protected cruisers became attractive for two reasons.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] First, the concept of the armored cruiser was not embraced wholeheartedly in naval circles.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Second, several navies were caught in a race between armor thickness and the size of main guns and did not have the money to spend on battleships and armored cruisers.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The use of smaller, cheaper cruisers was a better alternative.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The French navy adopted the protected cruiser wholeheartedly in the 1880s.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The *Jeune Ecole* school of thought, which proposed a navy composed of fast cruisers for commerce raiding and torpedo-boats for coast defense, was particularly influential in France.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The first French protected cruiser was *Sfax*, laid down in 1882, and followed by six classes of protected cruiser – and no armored cruisers until *Dupuy de Lôme*, laid down in 1888 but not finished until 1895.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] *Dupuy de Lôme* was a revolutionary ship, being the first French armored cruiser to dispose entirely of masts, and sheathed in steel armor.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] However, she and two others were not sufficiently seaworthy, and their armor could be penetrated by modern quick-firing guns.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Thus from 1891 to 1897 the French reverted to the construction of protected cruisers.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The British Royal Navy was equivocal about which protection scheme to use until 1887.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The large *Imperieuse* class, begun in 1881 and finished in 1886, were built as armored cruisers but were often referred to as protected cruisers.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] While they carried an armored belt some 10 in thick, the belt only covered 140 ft (43 m) of the 315 ft (96 m) length of the ship, and was submerged below the waterline at full load.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The real protection of the class came from the armored deck 4 in (102 mm) thick, and the arrangement of coal bunkers to prevent flooding.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] These ships were also the last armored cruisers to be designed with sails.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] However, on trials it became clear that the masts and sails did more harm than good; they were removed and replaced by a single military mast with machine guns.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The next class of small cruisers in the Royal Navy, the *Mersey* class, were protected cruisers, but the Royal Navy then returned to the armored cruiser with the *Orlando* class, begun in 1885 and completed in 1889.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The navy judged the *Orlando*s inferior to protected cruisers and built exclusively protected cruisers immediately afterwards, including some very large, fast ships like the 14,000-ton *Powerful* class.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] However, the *Orlando*s were the first class of cruiser to use the triple-expansion engine.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Because this type of reciprocating engine used the steam in three stages, it was more fuel-efficient than earlier compound engines.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] It also used steam of higher pressure, 60 poundforce per square inch, as compared to the 25 to 30 poundforce in earlier engines.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] With these engineering developments, warships could now dispense with sails and be entirely steam-driven.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The only major naval power to retain a preference for armored cruisers during the 1880s was Russia.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The Russian Navy laid down four armored cruisers and one protected cruiser during the decade, all being large ships with sails.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The development of rapid–fire cannons in the late 1880s forced a change in cruiser design.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Since a large number of hits at or near the waterline could negate the effect of water–excluding material used in protected cruisers, side armor again became a priority.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] However, it had to cover not just guns and the waterline but also much of the hull structure in–between; otherwise, the equally new high–explosive shells could penetrate and destroy much of the unarmored portion of the ship.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Another development was the publication in 1890 of American naval strategist Alfred Thayer Mahan's book *The Influence of Sea Power upon History*.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The armored cruisers built in the mid– to late–1890s were often as large and expensive as pre-dreadnought battleships.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] They combined long range, high speed and an armament approaching that of battleship with enough armor to protect them against quick-firing guns, considered the most important weapons afloat at the time.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Their speed was made possible due to another development, case-hardened steel armor—first Harvey armor and then crucially Krupp armor.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The higher tensile strength of these armors compared to nickel steel and mild steel made it feasible to put a light yet useful armor belt on a large cruiser.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] They saved further weight by not requiring a heavy timber backing, as previous armor plating had, to soften and spread the force of the impact from oncoming shells; 2.5 inches (64 mm) of teak to give a fair surface upon which to attach them was all that was needed.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Moreover, this belt could also be much wider than previously, covering the center of the hull, where the ammunition and engines were located, from the main deck to five feet below the waterline.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Steel bulkheads added strength to the hull, while armor as thick as the belt covered the guns and heavier protection surrounded the conning tower.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] With these improvements, the ships became more fully protected than was possible previously.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] They were also expensive to maintain at fighting strength as they required a greater number of stokers to feed the boilers than a battleship when steaming at flank speed.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The ideas presented by Mahan prompted French Admiral Ernest François Fournier to write his book *La flotte necessaire* in 1896.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Fournier argued that a fleet of technologically advanced armored cruisers and torpedo craft would be powerful and flexible enough to engage in a wide range of activity and overwhelm potential enemies.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] French naval and government circles embraced this ideal mutually and even advocates of battleships over cruisers admitted the latter's potential usefulness in scouting and commercial warfare.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The result was the building of increasingly large armored cruisers.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] *Jeanne d'Arc*, laid down in 1896, displaced 11,000 tons, carried a mixed armament of 194-millimetre (7.6 in) and 138-millimetre (5.4 in) guns, and had a 150-millimetre (5.9 in) belt of Harvey armor over her machinery spaces.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The 12,300-ton *Léon Gambetta* class and 14,000-ton *Edgar Quinet* class followed.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The *Edgar Quinet*s, slightly faster at 23 knots, were armed with 14 194-millimetre (7.6 in) guns and carried up to 170-millimetre (6.7 in) of armor on their belts, almost 100-millimetre (3.9 in) on their decks and 150-millimetre (5.9 in) on their turrets.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] At 21 knots, the *Cressy*s were slower than the newer French cruisers.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] However, their 6-inch (152 mm) belt of Krupp steel was expected to keep out armor-piercing shells from a 6-inch (152 mm) quick-firing gun at likely battle ranges, while their two 9.2-inch (233.7 mm) and 12 6-inch (152 mm) guns offered comparable firepower.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The 2,500-ton weight of their belt armor was an improvement over the 1809 tons of the otherwise similar *Diadem* class and very similar to that of the *Canopus* class of battleships.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The *Cressy*s were the beginning of a rapid expansion in British cruiser construction.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Between 1899 and 1905, seven classes of armored cruisers were either completed or laid down, a total of 35 ships.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Japan, which now received British technical assistance in naval matters and purchased larger vessels from France and Britain, began an armored cruiser program of its own.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The core of this 109-ship build-up was the "Six-Six Program" of six battleships and six (eventually eight) armored cruisers comparable to the British *Cressy* class.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] They were considered a compromise between cruiser and battleship and were intended to augment capital ship strength in battle squadrons.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] This practice would persist until World War I.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The first United States armored cruiser, USS *Maine*, was launched in 1889 but not completed until 1895 due to a three-year delay in the delivery of her armor plate.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] However, *Maine* was laid down before Harvey or Krupp armor was available and could not benefit from the advantage in weight these much lighter armors offered.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] She was redesignated a "second-class battleship" in 1894, an awkward compromise reflecting that, at 16.45 knots, she was considerably slower than other cruisers and weaker than first-line battleships.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Her destruction in Havana harbor in 1898 was a catalyst in starting the Spanish–American War.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Shortly after the war ended, the Navy laid down six *Pennsylvania*-class armored cruisers to take advantage of lessons learned and better control the large sea areas the nation had just gained.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Much larger than their predecessors (displacing 14,500 tons as compared to 8150 for *New York*), the *Pennsylvania*s "were closer to light battleships than to cruisers," according to naval historian William Friedman.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] They carried four 8-inch (203 mm) and 14 6-inch (152 mm) guns, 6 inches (152 mm) of armor on their belts, 6.5 inches (165 mm) on their turrets and 9 inches (229 mm) on their conning towers.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Their deck armor was light at 1.5 inches (38 mm) for flat surfaces and 3 inches (76 mm) for sloped, a compromise made for faster speed (22 knots, compared with 20 knots for *Brooklyn*).
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Improved ammunition made their main guns as powerful as the 12-inch (305 mm) guns of the battleship *Iowa* and their use of state instead of city names, usually reserved for capital ships, emphasized their kinship.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] More often, they were seen fighting in a battle line.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] They would not been seen in their designed role until World War I.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Even with all their improvements and apparent performance, opinion on the armored cruiser was mixed.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Navy in hearings before the House of Representatives gave testimony to the effect that no armored cruisers were further planned nor to it knowledge were armored cruisers being built by any major naval power worldwide.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Armored cruisers were used with success in the line of battle by the Japanese at the Battle of Tsushima in 1905.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Of the battle damage received by the Japanese, the armored cruiser *Nisshin* received eight hits, which destroyed three of her 8-inch (203 mm) guns, killed five crew members and injured 90 more (one of the wounded being Isoroku Yamamoto, who would later plan the attack on Pearl Harbor).
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] None of the other Japanese armored cruisers suffered serious damage or large loss of life.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] *Iwate* was hit 16 times but no one onboard was killed and only 15 were wounded.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Except for *Kasagi*, all the cruisers present at Tsushima that morning were still battle-ready in the evening.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Danish Navy Commander William Hovgaard, who would later become president of New York Shipbuilding and serve on the U.S.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Buoyed with their success at Tsushima, Japan laid down the four *Tsukuba*-class cruisers between 1905 and 1908.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] At a speed of 20.5 knots, they carried an extremely heavy main armament of four 12-inch (305 mm) guns, 8 inches (203 mm) of belt and turret armor and 3 inches (76 mm) of deck armor.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The *Tsukuba*s were intended to take the place of aging battleships and thus showed Japan's intention of continuing to use armored cruisers in fleet engagements.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Navy raised the main gun caliber of its cruisers with its *Tennessee* class, laid down between 1902 and 1904.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] These mounted four 10-inch (254 mm) and 16 6-inch (152 mm) guns, the former a size previously allocated to battleships.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] While they had thinner armor than the *Pennsylvania*s (5 inches (127 mm) on their belts and 1 inch (25 mm) on their decks) due to newly imposed congressional restraints on tonnage, they could still steam at 22 knots.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] They were built as a fast, powerful response in the eventuality of a Pacific war and were the largest and last American armored cruisers built.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The British also considered 10-inch (254 mm) and 12-inch (305 mm) guns for its *Minotaur*-class cruisers, the culmination of its armored cruiser building program.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] They displaced 14,600 tons, were capable of 23 knots and were armed with four 9.2-inch (234 mm) and 10 7.5-inch (191 mm) guns.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] By the time these ships were commissioned, Britain possessed the largest armored cruiser force in the world.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Undaunted and fully engaged in a naval arms race with the British, the Germans also continued to build armored cruisers, partly from their faith in them as fighting units and commerce raiders, partly from Japan's success.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Between 1897 and 1906 they laid down eight of them for use on overseas stations.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The initial two, SMS *Fürst Bismarck* and SMS *Prinz Heinrich*, were armed with 9.44-inch (240 mm) guns; the six that followed had 8.2-inch (208 mm) guns of a more modern design.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The final pair, *Scharnhorst* and *Gneisenau*, displaced 12,781 tons, steamed at 23.5 knots, carried 6 inches (152 mm) of belt and 2 inches (51 mm) of deck armor and were armed with eight 8.2-inch (208 mm) guns.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Another powerful armored cruiser was the Russian *Rurik*, completed in 1908.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Armed with four 10-inch (254 mm) in two twin turrets fore and aft and eight 8-inch (203 mm) in turrets along the ship's sides, she displaced 15,190 tons and carried a 6-inch (152 mm) belt, two armored decks and 8-inch (203 mm) armor on her turrets and conning tower.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] *Rurik* was unusual in that she was Russian designed but British built; the Russian Navy was not usually a customer of British shipyards.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] She was reportedly one of the best armored cruisers built, with an advanced sprinkler protection for the magazines.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Intended as the first of a three-ship class, *Rurik*'s sisters were cancelled with the advent of the battlecruiser HMS *Invincible*.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] "The supreme embodiment of the armored cruiser," in historian Robert K.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Massie's words, was the German ship SMS *Blücher*.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] An enlarged version of the *Scharnhorst* class with a speed of 24.25 knots, armed with 12 8.2-inch (208 mm) and eight 5.9-inch (150 mm) guns, *Blücher* was planned as an armored cruiser in part because the British had misled the Germans on the *Invincible*s then being constructed.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The Germans expected these new British ships to be armed with six or eight 9.2 in (23 cm) guns.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] One week after the final decision to construct *Blücher*, the German naval attache learned they would carry eight 30.5 cm (12.0 in) guns, the same type mounted on battleships.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] With no funds available to redesign *Blücher*, work was ordered to proceed as scheduled.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Although much more powerful than a typical armored cruiser, she was significantly weaker than the new British battlecruisers.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] By the time these new armored cruisers were entering service, such types of ships had reached the end of its development.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Thirty percent was the ratio by which frigates had been faster than ships of the line in the days of sail.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] If a battleship sailed at 20 knots, this would mean that an armored cruiser would have to steam at least 26 or 27 knots.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] To fulfill these criteria, however, armored cruisers would have to be built much larger and take on a different form than they had in the past.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] First Sea Lord "Jacky" Fisher, an advocate of armored cruisers as more useful than battleships to safeguard British trade and territorial interests, saw his efforts justified; his belief that "speed is armor" would lead him to create the battlecruiser.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The battlecruiser HMS *Invincible* and her two sister ships were designed specifically to fulfill these requirements.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Because they carried the heavy guns normally ascribed to battleships, they could also theoretically hold their place in a battle line more readily than armored cruisers and serve as the "battleship-cruiser" for which Hovgaard had argued after Tsushima.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] All these factors made battlecruisers attractive fighting units, although Britain, Germany and Japan would be the only powers to build them.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] They also meant that the armored cruiser as it had been known was now outmoded and no more were built after 1910.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Later in the same address is this: "Every argument used against [armored cruisers] holds true for battle-cruisers of the *Invincible* type, except that the latter, if wounded, would be fit to lie in the line, owing to her great armament.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Although pre-dreadnought battleships and armored cruisers were outclassed by modern battleship and battlecruiser designs, respectively, armored cruisers still played an active role in World War I.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Their armor and firepower was sufficient to defeat other cruiser types and armed merchant vessels, while their speed and range made them particularly useful for extended operations out in the high seas.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Some German and Royal Navy vessels, like HMS *Good Hope*, were allocated to remote naval squadrons.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Many other vessels however, were formed into independent squadrons for patrolling European waters and accompanied capital ships every time the latter made forays out of port.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] At the Battle of Coronel, the German armored cruisers SMS *Scharnhorst* and SMS *Gneisenau* scored a resounding victory over British naval forces from the West Indies Station.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] With newer ships, superior gunnery and optimal logistics, the Germans sank the Royal Navy armored cruisers HMS *Monmouth* and HMS *Good Hope*, with the loss of over 1,500 British sailors and officers (including Rear-Admiral Christopher Cradock).
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] This was one of the last battles involving armored cruisers as the chief adversaries; all subsequent engagements were dominated by battlecruisers and dreadnought battleships.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Moreover, the timing could not have been worse for British morale.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Six weeks earlier, the armored cruisers HMS *Cressy*, HMS *Hogue* and HMS *Aboukir* had all been sunk on the same day by the German submarine U-9.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Five weeks later, the Battle of the Falkland Islands showed graphically how much technology and tactics had changed.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] SMS *Scharnhorst* and SMS *Gneisenau* were sunk by a British force of the battlecruisers HMS *Invincible* and HMS *Inflexible*, three armoured cruisers and two light cruisers.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The German armored cruisers were too slow to outrun their pursuers, and their initially accurate gunnery failed to inflict serious damage on the British battlecruisers.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The British 12-inch guns turned the tide of battle once they started scoring hits on the Germans, and the German armored cruisers were fatally crippled before they had a chance to close the range and use their superior secondary armament.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] This victory seemed to validate Lord "Jacky" Fisher's justification in building battlecruisers—to track down and destroy armored cruisers with vessels possessing superior speed and firepower.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The German force commander Admiral Maximilian von Spee had been wary of the Allies' battlecruisers, especially the Imperial Japanese Navy and the Royal Australian Navy—in fact he described the latter's flagship, the battlecruiser HMAS *Australia*, as being superior to his entire force by itself.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] At the Falklands, he had already deduced the battle was lost when he missed the chance to attack the British battlecruisers in port.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] During the Battle of Dogger Bank, *Blücher* was crippled by a shell from a British battlecruiser, which slowed *Blücher* to 17 knots and eventually sealed her fate.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Admiral Franz von Hipper chose to let *Blücher* go down so his more valuable battlecruisers could escape.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] HMS *Warrior*, HMS *Defence* and HMS *Black Prince* were lost at the Battle of Jutland when they inadvertently came into sight and range of the German Navy's battle line, which included several battlecruisers and dreadnought battleships.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The armor belt was shown to be far less than required to survive the 280mm (11 inch) and 300 mm (12 inch) shells of more modern dreadnoughts and battlecruisers and the cruisers were too slow to get away from them.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The final nail in the coffin for the armored cruiser type was in the development of capped armor-piercing shells.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The Harvey and Krupp Cemented armor that had looked to offer protection failed when hit with soft capped AP shells of large enough size.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Later hard capped AP shell would only make the matter worse.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] After the end of World War I, many of the surviving armored cruisers were sold for scrap.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The Washington Naval Treaty of 1922 placed strict limits on the numbers of "capital ships" possessed by the navies of the great powers.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] A "capital ship" was defined as any vessel of over 10,000 tons displacement or with guns over 8-in caliber, and several more armored cruisers were decommissioned to comply with the terms of the treaty.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The London Naval Treaty of 1930 introduced further limits on cruiser tonnage, and the former role of the armored cruiser was occupied by more modern light cruisers and heavy cruisers (and, in the case of the German navy, panzerschiffe).
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The Hellenic Navy's *Georgios Averof*, constructed in 1909, served with the British Navy as a convoy escort in the Indian Ocean after the fall of Greece, while a number of Japanese armored cruisers were still active as minelayers or training vessels.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The Imperial Japanese Navy armored cruisers *Asama*, *Izumo*, *Tokiwa*, *Iwate*, *Yakumo*, *Azuma*, & *Kasuga* were used as training, support, and anti-aircraft ships during the war near the Japanese home islands.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Most were sunk by Allied bombings in Japanese harbors.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The Regia Marina's *San Giorgio* was deployed to Spain to protected Italian interests during the Spanish Civil War.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] During World War II, she was heavily utilized at the Siege of Tobruk.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] There she provided anti-aircraft cover and naval gunfire support to Italian units.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] She was heavily damaged by British aircraft and was scuttled to prevent her capture.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Her sister ship, *San Marco* was decommissioned in 1931 and used as a radio controlled target ship.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] In 1943, she was scuttled to prevent her capture by the Germans.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The United States Navy's USS *Rochester*, decommissioned since 1933, was moored in Subic Bay and used as a receiving ship and anti-aircraft platform.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] She was later scuttled to prevent her capture by the Japanese during the Invasion of The Philippines.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The Argentine Navy's ARA *General Belgrano* and ARA *Pueyrredón* served until 1947 and 1954 respectfully.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The Swedish Navy's HSwMS *Fylgia* underwent an extensive modernization from 1939 to 1940 and conducted neutrality patrols in the Baltic Sea during World War II.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The only armored cruiser still considered to be in existence, as well as in active duty, is the aforementioned *Georgios Averof*, preserved as a museum in Palaio Faliro, Greece.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The armored cruiser was not a close ancestor of heavy cruisers, even though the name might suggest this.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The armored cruiser type had come about in a time of transition as one technology after another presented itself.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Boilers had become better (though still in need of improvement), and Krupp cemented armor and compound steam engines had arrived.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The rate of change was nothing less than staggering and any ship more than 20 years old was found to be completely obsolete.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] The Italian Navy, unable to afford battleships, produced the *Garibaldi*-class cruiser of 7,500 tons displacement which was an international success.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] White DNC of the British Royal Navy was taken by the design and presented the design for the *Cressy*-class cruiser of 12,000 tons displacement designed from the onset as an adjunct to the pre-dreadnought battle line, on 3 May 1897.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] As such the armored cruiser is the direct predecessor of and inspiration for the battlecruiser.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] There were also important technical differences between the heavy cruiser and the armored cruiser, some of which reflected the generational gap between them.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Heavy cruisers were typically powered by oil-fired superheated steam boilers and steam turbine engines, and were capable of far faster speeds than armored cruisers (propelled by coal-fired reciprocating steam engines of their era) ever had been.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Countries withdrawing from the Washington Treaty and the London Naval Treaty of 1930 and Second London Naval Treaty 1936 eventually rendered all limitations on heavy cruisers moot, although the only supersized or large cruisers actually built were the two members of the *Alaska* class.
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] Armored cruisers were often pressed into the main line of battle against battlecruisers and dreadnought battleships (battles of the Falkland Islands, Dogger Bank and Jutland).
[src:conning-tower/armored-cruiser] By contrast, heavy cruisers and light cruisers were not expected to be deployed as such, although there had been some notable engagements (battles of the Denmark Strait, Matapan, Guadalcanal and Surigao Strait).
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] On December 7, 1941, the Empire of Japan launched a surprise military strike on the United States Pacific Fleet at its naval base at Pearl Harbor on Oahu, Hawaii Territory.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At the time, the US was a neutral country in World War II.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The air raid on Pearl Harbor, which was launched from aircraft carriers, prompted the US to declare war on Japan the next day.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Japanese military leadership referred to the attack as the **Hawaii Operation** and **Operation AI**, and as **Operation Z** during its planning.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The attack on Pearl Harbor was preceded by months of negotiations between the US and Japan over the future of the Pacific.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japanese demands included that the US end its sanctions against Japan, cease aiding China in the Second Sino-Japanese War, and allow Japan access to the resources of the Dutch East Indies.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japan dispatched its naval attack group on November 26, 1941, just before receiving the Hull note, which stated the US desire that Japan withdraw from China and French Indochina.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Isoroku Yamamoto, commander of the Japanese Combined Fleet, planned the attack as a pre-emptive strike on the Pacific Fleet, which had been based at Pearl Harbor since 1940 in order to prevent it from interfering with Japan's planned actions in Southeast Asia.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Yamamoto hoped that the strike would enable Japan to make rapid territorial gains and negotiate peace.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In addition to Pearl Harbor, over seven hours Japan launched coordinated attacks on the US-held Philippines, Guam, and Wake Island, as well as on the British Empire in Malaya, Singapore, and Hong Kong.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The attacking force, commanded by Chūichi Nagumo, launched its attack at 7:48 a.m.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The base was struck by 353 fighters, level and dive bombers, and torpedo bombers in two waves launched from six aircraft carriers.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Of the eight US battleships present, all were damaged and four were sunk.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] All but the USS *Arizona* and the USS *Utah* were later refloated, and six were returned to service during the war.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Japanese also sank or damaged three cruisers, three destroyers, an anti-aircraft training ship, and a minelayer.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] More than 180 US aircraft were destroyed.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A total of 2,403 Americans were killed and 1,178 others were wounded.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japanese losses totaled 29 aircraft, five midget submarines, and 130 personnel.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The three US carriers assigned to Pearl Harbor were at sea at the time, and important base installations, including its oil storage and naval repair facilities, were not attacked.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japan declared war on the US and the British Empire later that day (December 8 in Tokyo), but the declarations were not delivered until the next day.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] On December 8, both the United Kingdom and the US declared war on Japan.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] On December 11, though they had no formal obligation to do so under the Tripartite Pact with Japan, Germany and Italy each declared war on the United States, which responded by declaring war on Germany and Italy.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] While there were historical precedents for unannounced military action by Japan, the lack of a formal warning and perception that the attack had been unprovoked led US President Franklin D.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Roosevelt to famously label December 7, 1941, "a date which will live in infamy".
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The attack remains the deadliest event to ever happen in Hawaii, and for nearly 60 years, was the deadliest foreign attack on the US until the September 11 attacks in 2001.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] War between the Empire of Japan and the United States was seen as a possibility since the 1920s.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japan had been wary of American territorial and military expansion in the Pacific and Asia since the late 1890s, followed by the annexation of islands, such as Hawaii and the Philippines, which were close to or within Japan's perceived sphere of influence.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At the same time, Japanese strategic thinkers believed that Japan needed economic self-sufficiency in order to wage modern war.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The experiences of World War I had taught the Japanese that modern wars would be protracted, require total mobilization, and create vulnerabilities for trade embargoes and encirclement.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] As a consequence, Japan needed access to strategically important resources (e.g., iron, oil) that could not be extracted at sufficient levels in the home islands.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Although Japan had begun to take a hostile stance against the United States after the rejection of the Racial Equality Proposal, their relationship was cordial enough to remain trading partners.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Tensions did not seriously grow until Japan's invasion of Manchuria in 1931.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Over the next decade, Japan expanded into China, leading to the Second Sino-Japanese War in 1937.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japan spent considerable effort trying to isolate China and endeavored to secure enough independent resources to attain victory on the mainland.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The "Southern Operation" was designed to assist these efforts.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Nevertheless, Japan would still rely heavily on US oil imports, including to Japanese forces in Japan-occupied Manchuria.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In a memorandum dated October 24, 1934, Chief of the Division of Far Eastern Affairs Stanley K.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Hornbeck discussed his meeting with Standard Oil New Jersey head Walter C.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The memo described that Teagle was uncooperative with US recommendations and how Standard Oil was given special treatment by the Japanese government, which made the company less subject to Japan's national business regulation policies than other companies.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Starting in December 1937, events such as the Japanese attack on USS *Panay*, the Allison incident, and the Rape of Nanjing swung Western public opinion sharply against Japan.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The United States unsuccessfully proposed a joint action with the United Kingdom to blockade Japan.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In 1938, following an appeal by President Roosevelt, American companies stopped providing Japan with implements of war.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In 1940, Japan invaded French Indochina, attempting to stymie the flow of supplies reaching China.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The United States halted shipments of airplanes, parts, machine tools, and aviation gasoline to Japan, which Japan perceived as an unfriendly act.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The United States did not stop oil exports, however, partly because of the prevailing sentiment in Washington that given Japanese dependence on American oil, such an action was likely to be considered an extreme provocation.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Roosevelt moved the Pacific Fleet from San Diego to Hawaii.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] He also ordered a military buildup in the Philippines, taking both actions in the hope of discouraging Japanese aggression in the Far East.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Because the Japanese high command was mistakenly certain any attack on the United Kingdom's Southeast Asian colonies, including Singapore, would bring the United States into the war, a devastating preventive strike appeared to be the only way to prevent American naval interference.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] An invasion of the Philippines was also considered necessary by Japanese war planners.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The American War Plan Orange had envisioned defending the Philippines with an elite force of 40,000 men; this option was never implemented due to opposition from Douglas MacArthur, who felt he would need a force ten times that size.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] By 1941, American planners expected to have to abandon the Philippines at the outbreak of war.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Hart, commander of the United States Asiatic Fleet, was given orders to that effect.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The United States finally ceased oil exports to Japan in July 1941, following the seizure of French Indochina after the Fall of France, in part because of new American restrictions on domestic oil consumption.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Because of this decision, Japan proceeded with plans to take the oil-rich Dutch East Indies.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] On August 17, Roosevelt warned Japan that America was prepared to take opposing steps if "neighboring countries" were attacked.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japan and the United States engaged in negotiations during 1941, attempting to improve relations.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In the course of these negotiations, Japan offered to withdraw from most of China and Indochina after making peace with the Nationalist government.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] It also proposed to adopt an independent interpretation of the Tripartite Pact and to refrain from trade discrimination, provided all other nations reciprocated.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japanese Prime Minister Konoe then offered to meet with Roosevelt, but Roosevelt insisted on reaching an agreement before any meeting.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The American ambassador to Japan repeatedly urged Roosevelt to accept the meeting, warning that it was the only way to preserve the conciliatory Konoe government and peace in the Pacific.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] However, his recommendation was not acted upon.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Konoe government collapsed the following month when the Japanese military rejected a withdrawal of all troops from China.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The American counter-proposal of November 26 (November 27 in Japan), the Hull note, required Japan to completely evacuate China without conditions and conclude non-aggression pacts with Pacific powers.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] On November 26 in Japan, the day before the note's delivery, the Japanese task force left port for Pearl Harbor.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Japanese intended the attack as a preventive action to keep the United States Pacific Fleet from interfering with their planned military actions in Southeast Asia against overseas territories of the United Kingdom, the Netherlands, and the United States.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Over the course of seven hours, there were coordinated Japanese attacks on the American-held Philippines, Guam, Wake Island, Midway Atoll and on the British Empire in Malaya, Singapore, and Hong Kong.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Preliminary planning for an attack on Pearl Harbor to protect the move into the "Southern Resource Area", the Japanese term for the Dutch East Indies and Southeast Asia generally, began early in 1941 under the auspices of Admiral Isoroku Yamamoto, then commanding Japan's Combined Fleet.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] He won assent to formal planning and training for an attack from the Imperial Japanese Navy General Staff only after much contention with Naval Headquarters, including a threat to resign his command.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Full-scale planning was underway by early spring 1941, primarily by Rear Admiral Ryūnosuke Kusaka, with assistance from Commander Minoru Genda and Yamamoto's Deputy Chief of Staff, Captain Kameto Kuroshima.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The planners studied the 1940 British air attack on the Italian fleet at Taranto intensively.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Over the next several months, pilots were trained, equipment was adapted, and intelligence was collected.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Despite these preparations, Emperor Hirohito did not approve the attack plan until November 5, after the third of four Imperial Conferences called to consider the matter.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At first, he hesitated to engage in war but eventually authorized the Pearl Harbor strike despite dissent from certain advisors.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Final authorization was not given by the emperor until December 1, after a majority of Japanese leaders advised him the Hull note would "destroy the fruits of the China incident, endanger Manchukuo and undermine Japanese control of Korea".
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Before the attack, he became more involved in military matters, even joining the Conference of Military Councillors, which was considered unusual for him.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Additionally, he actively sought more information about the war plans.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] According to an aide, he openly displayed happiness upon hearing about the success of the surprise attacks.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] By late 1941, many observers believed that hostilities between the United States and Japan were imminent.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A Gallup poll just before the attack on Pearl Harbor found that 52% of Americans expected war with Japan, 27% did not, and 21% had no opinion.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] While American Pacific bases and facilities had been placed on alert on many occasions, officials doubted Pearl Harbor would be the first target; instead, they expected the Philippines to be attacked first.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] This presumption was due to the threat that the air bases throughout that country and the naval base at Manila posed to sea lanes, as well as to the shipment of supplies to Japan from territory to the south.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] They also incorrectly believed that Japan was not capable of mounting more than one major naval operation at a time.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Japanese attack had several major aims.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] First, it intended to destroy important American fleet units, thereby preventing the Pacific Fleet from interfering with the Japanese conquest of the Dutch East Indies and Malaya and enabling Japan to conquer Southeast Asia without interference.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The leaders of the Imperial Japanese Navy (IJN) subscribed to Alfred Thayer Mahan's "decisive battle" doctrine, especially that of destroying the maximum number of battleships.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Second, it was hoped to buy time for Japan to consolidate its position and increase its naval strength before shipbuilding authorized by the 1940 Vinson-Walsh Act erased any chance of victory.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Third, to deliver a blow to America's ability to mobilize its forces in the Pacific, battleships were chosen as the main targets, since they were the prestige ships of navies at the time.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Finally, it was hoped that the attack would undermine American morale to such an extent that the American government would drop its demands contrary to Japanese interests and seek a peace compromise.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A further disadvantage would prove to be the unexpected absence of all three Pacific Fleet aircraft carriers (*Enterprise*, *Lexington*, and *Saratoga*).
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Despite these concerns, Yamamoto decided to press ahead.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japanese confidence in their ability to win a short war meant that other targets in the harbor, especially the navy yard, oil tank farms and submarine base, were left unscathed, since by their thinking the war would be over before the influence of these facilities would be felt.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Japanese plan was for the fleet to steam to a position northwest of Hawaii, and attack Pearl Harbor with aircraft.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The attack would consist of about 360 aircraft in two waves.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] 48 fighter aircraft would remain as defensive combat air patrol (CAP) over the fleet.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The first wave of 180 aircraft was to be the primary attack.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The level bombers in this wave were armed with armor-piercing bombs or specially adapted Type 91 aerial torpedoes equipped with an anti-roll mechanism and a rudder extension to operate in the shallow water of Pearl Harbor.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The level bombers were to attack battleships and aircraft carriers, or if these were not present, cruisers and destroyers.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The dive bombers were to attack land targets with general purpose (GP) bombs.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The fighters were to strafe airfields, destroying aircraft on the ground, and engage any that got into the air, thus preventing any interference with the bombers.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The second wave of 180 aircraft was to be similar, but carry only GP bombs and mainly strike airfields.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] They would target carriers first, cruisers second, and battleships third.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Returning fighters were to refuel and then join the CAP over the fleet.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Before launching the attack, the Strike Force would launch two reconnaissance floatplanes from heavy cruisers *Chikuma* and *Tone*, to scout Oahu and Lahaina Roads near Maui, respectively.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Some historians think these reconnaissance aircraft flights risked alerting the Americans, and were not necessary.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Fleet composition and preparedness information in Pearl Harbor were already known from the reports of the Japanese spy Takeo Yoshikawa.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Fleet submarines *I-16*, *I-18*, *I-20*, *I-22*, and *I-24* each embarked a Type A midget submarine for transport to the waters off Oahu.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The five I-boats left Kure Naval District on November 25, 1941.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] On December 6, they came to within 10 nmi (19 km; 12 mi) of the mouth of Pearl Harbor and launched their midget subs at about 01:00 local time on December 7.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At 03:42 Hawaiian time, the minesweeper *Condor* spotted a midget submarine periscope southwest of the Pearl Harbor entrance buoy and alerted the destroyer *Ward*.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The midget may have entered Pearl Harbor.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] However, *Ward* sank another midget submarine at 06:37 in the first American shots in the Pacific Theater.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A midget submarine on the north side of Ford Island missed the seaplane tender *Curtiss* with her first torpedo and missed the attacking destroyer *Monaghan* with her other one before being sunk by *Monaghan* at 08:43.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A third midget submarine, *Ha-19*, grounded twice, once outside the harbor entrance and again on the east side of Oahu, where it was captured on December 8.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Ensign Kazuo Sakamaki swam ashore and was captured by Hawaii National Guard Corporal David Akui, becoming the first Japanese prisoner of war.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A fourth had been damaged by a depth charge attack and was abandoned by its crew before it could fire its torpedoes.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] It was found outside the harbor in 1960.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Japanese forces received a radio message from a midget submarine at 00:41 on December 8 claiming to have damaged one or more large warships inside Pearl Harbor.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In 1992, 2000, and 2001, Hawaii Undersea Research Laboratory's submersibles found the wreck of the fifth midget submarine lying in three parts outside Pearl Harbor.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The wreck was in the debris field where much surplus American equipment had been dumped after the war, including vehicles and landing craft.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] This correlates with reports of two torpedoes fired at the light cruiser *St.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Louis* at 10:04 at the entrance of Pearl Harbor, and a possible torpedo fired at destroyer *Helm* at 08:21.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] There is dispute over this official chain of events though.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Louis* saw was also reportedly a porpoising minesweeping float being towed by the destroyer *Boggs*.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Admiral Chester Nimitz, in a report to Congress, confirmed that one midget submarine's torpedo (possibly from the other midget submarine that fired torpedoes but failed to hit a target) which was fired but did not explode was recovered in Pearl Harbor and was much larger than the aerial torpedoes.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The attack took place before any formal declaration of war was made by Japan, but this was not Admiral Yamamoto's intention.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] He originally stipulated that the attack should not commence until thirty minutes after Japan had informed the United States that peace negotiations were at an end.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] However, the attack began before the notice could be delivered.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Tokyo transmitted the 5000-word notification (commonly called the "14-Part Message") in two blocks to the Japanese Embassy in Washington.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Transcribing the message took too long for the Japanese ambassador to deliver it at 1:00 p.m.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Washington time, as ordered, and consequently the message was not presented until more than one hour after the attack had begun — but American code breakers had already deciphered and translated most of the message hours before it was scheduled to be delivered.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The final part of the message is sometimes described as a declaration of war.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] While it was viewed by a number of senior American government and military officials as a very strong indicator negotiations were likely to be terminated and that war might break out at any moment, it neither declared war nor severed diplomatic relations.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A declaration of war was printed on the front page of Japan's newspapers in the evening edition of December 8 (late December 7 in the United States), but not delivered to the American government until the day after the attack.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] For decades, conventional wisdom held that Japan attacked without first formally breaking diplomatic relations only because of accidents and bumbling that delayed the delivery of a document hinting at war to Washington.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In any event, even if the Japanese had decoded and delivered the 14-Part Message before the beginning of the attack, it would not have constituted either a formal break of diplomatic relations or a declaration of war.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] United States naval intelligence officers were alarmed by the unusual timing for delivering the message — 1:00 p.m. on a Sunday, which was 7:30 a.m. in Hawaii — and attempted to alert Pearl Harbor.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] But due to communication problems the warning was not delivered before the attack.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The first attack wave of 183 airplanes, led by Commander Mitsuo Fuchida, was launched north of Oahu.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Six airplanes failed to launch due to technical difficulties.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] As the first wave approached Oahu, it was detected by United States Army SCR-270 radar positioned at Opana Point near the island's northern tip.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] This post had been in training mode for months, but was not yet operational.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The operators, Privates George Elliot Jr. and Joseph Lockard, reported a target to Private Joseph P.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] McDonald, who was stationed at Fort Shafter's Intercept Center near Pearl Harbor Lieutenant Kermit A.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Tyler, a newly assigned officer at the thinly manned Intercept Center, presumed it was the scheduled arrival of six B-17 bombers from California.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Japanese planes were approaching from a direction very close (only a few degrees difference) to that of the bombers, and while the operators had never seen a formation as large on radar, they neglected to tell Tyler of its size.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Tyler, for security reasons, could not tell the operators of the six B-17s that were due (even though it was widely known).
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] As the first wave approached Oahu, they encountered and shot down several small American civilian aircraft.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At least one of these radioed a somewhat incoherent warning.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Other warnings from ships off the harbor entrance were still being processed or awaiting confirmation when the Japanese air assault began at 7:48 a.m.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] December 8 Japanese Standard Time, as kept by ships of the *Kido Butai*), with the attack on Kaneohe.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A total of 353 Japanese planes reached Oahu in two waves.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The 171 planes in the second wave attacked the Army Air Forces' Bellows Field, near Kaneohe on the windward side of the island, and Ford Island.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The only aerial opposition came from a handful of P-36 Hawks, P-40 Warhawks and some SBD Dauntless dive bombers from the carrier *Enterprise*.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In the first-wave attack, about eight of the forty-nine 800‑kg (1760 lb) armor-piercing bombs dropped hit their intended battleship targets.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At least two of those bombs broke up on impact, another detonated before penetrating an unarmored deck, and one was a dud.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Thirteen of the forty torpedoes hit battleships, while four hit other ships.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Men aboard the ships awoke to the sounds of alarms, bombs exploding, and gunfire, prompting them to dress as they ran to General Quarters stations.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] (The famous message "Air raid Pearl Harbor.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] This is not drill." was sent from the headquarters of Patrol Wing Two, the first senior Hawaiian command to respond.) American servicemen were caught unprepared by the attack.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Ammunition lockers were locked, aircraft parked wingtip to wingtip in the open to prevent sabotage, guns unmanned (none of the Navy's 5"/38s, only a quarter of its machine guns, and only four of 31 Army batteries got in action).
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Despite this low alert status, many American military personnel responded effectively during the attack.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Ensign Joseph Taussig Jr., aboard *Nevada*, commanded the ship's antiaircraft guns and was severely wounded but remained at his post.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Thomas commanded *Nevada* in the captain's absence and got her underway until the ship was grounded at 9:10 a.m.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] One of the destroyers, *Aylwin*, got underway with only four officers aboard, all ensigns, none with more than a year's sea duty; she operated at sea for 36 hours before her commanding officer managed to get back aboard.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Captain Mervyn Bennion, commanding *West Virginia*, led his men until he was cut down by fragments from a bomb which hit *Tennessee*, moored alongside.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The second planned wave consisted of 171 planes: 54 B5Ns, 81 D3As, and 36 A6Ms, commanded by Lieutenant-Commander Shigekazu Shimazaki.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Four planes failed to launch because of technical difficulties.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The second wave was divided into three groups.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] One was tasked to attack Kāneʻohe, the rest Pearl Harbor proper.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The separate sections arrived at the attack point almost simultaneously from several directions.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] was sunk by six torpedoes and two bombs during the attack.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Ninety minutes after it began, the attack was over.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] 2,008 sailors were killed and 710 others wounded; 218 soldiers and airmen (who were part of the Army before the independent United States Air Force in 1947) were killed and 364 wounded; 109 Marines were killed and 69 wounded; and 68 civilians were killed and 35 wounded.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In total, 2,403 Americans were killed, and 1,178 were wounded.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Eighteen ships were sunk or run aground, including five battleships.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] All of the Americans killed or wounded during the attack were legally non-combatants, given that there was no state of war when the attack occurred.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Of the American fatalities, nearly half were due to the explosion of *Arizona*'s forward magazine after she was hit by a modified 16-inch (410 mm) shell.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Author Craig Nelson wrote that the vast majority of the US sailors killed at Pearl Harbor were junior enlisted personnel.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] "The officers of the Navy all lived in houses and the junior people were the ones on the boats, so pretty much all of the people who died in the direct line of the attack were very junior people", Nelson said.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Among the notable civilian casualties were nine Honolulu Fire Department firefighters who responded to Hickam Field during the bombing in Honolulu, becoming the only fire department members on American soil to be attacked by a foreign power in history.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Fireman Harry Tuck Lee Pang of Engine 6 was killed near the hangars by machine-gun fire from a Japanese plane.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Captains Thomas Macy and John Carreira of Engine 4 and Engine 1, respectively, died while battling flames inside the hangar after a Japanese bomb crashed through the roof.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] An additional six firefighters were wounded by Japanese shrapnel.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] This made the nine men the only non-military firefighters to receive such an award in American history.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Already damaged by a torpedo and on fire amidships, *Nevada* attempted to exit the harbor.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] She was targeted by many Japanese bombers as she got underway and sustained more hits from 250 lb (113 kg) bombs, which started further fires.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] She was deliberately beached to avoid risking blocking the harbor entrance if she sank there.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] *California* was hit by two bombs and two torpedoes.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The crew might have kept her afloat, but were ordered to abandon ship just as they were raising power for the pumps.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Burning oil from *Arizona* and *West Virginia* was drifted down toward her and probably made the situation look worse than it was.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The disarmed target ship *Utah* was holed twice by torpedoes.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] *West Virginia* was hit by seven torpedoes, the seventh tearing away her rudder.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] *Oklahoma* was hit by four torpedoes, the last two above her belt armor, which caused her to capsize.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] *Maryland* was hit by two of the converted 16" shells, but neither caused serious damage.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Although the Japanese concentrated on battleships (the largest vessels present), they did not ignore other targets.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The light cruiser *Helena* was torpedoed, and the concussion from the blast capsized the neighboring minelayer *Oglala*.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Two destroyers in dry dock, *Cassin* and *Downes*, were destroyed when bombs penetrated their fuel bunkers.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The leaking fuel caught fire; flooding the dry dock in an effort to fight fire made the burning oil rise, and both were burned out.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] *Cassin* slipped from her keel blocks and rolled against *Downes*.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The light cruiser *Raleigh* was holed by a torpedo.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The light cruiser *Honolulu* was damaged but remained in service.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The repair vessel *Vestal*, moored alongside *Arizona*, was heavily damaged and beached.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The seaplane tender *Curtiss* was also damaged.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The destroyer *Shaw* was badly damaged when two bombs penetrated her forward magazine.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Of the 402 American aircraft in Hawaii, 188 were destroyed and 159 damaged, 155 of them on the ground.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Almost none were actually ready to take off to defend the base.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Eight Army Air Forces pilots managed to get airborne during the attack, and six were credited with downing at least one Japanese aircraft during the attack: 1st Lieutenant Lewis M.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Of 33 Consolidated PBY Catalinas in Hawaii, 30 were destroyed, while three on patrol at the time of the attack returned undamaged.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Friendly fire brought down some American planes on top of that, including four from an inbound flight from *Enterprise*.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At the time of the attack, nine civilian aircraft were flying in the vicinity of Pearl Harbor.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Fifty-five Japanese airmen and nine submariners were killed in the attack, and one, Kazuo Sakamaki, was captured.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Of Japan's 414 available planes, 350 took part in the raid.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Twenty-nine were lost, nine in the first wave (three fighters, one dive bomber, and five torpedo bombers) and twenty in the second (six fighters and fourteen dive bombers), with another 74 damaged by anti-aircraft fire from the ground.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] According to some accounts, several Japanese junior officers, including Fuchida and Genda, urged Nagumo to carry out a third strike in order to sink more of Pearl Harbor's remaining warships, and damage the base's maintenance shops, drydock facilities and oil tank yards.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Most notably, Fuchida gave a firsthand account of this meeting several times after the war.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] However, some historians have cast doubt on this and many other of Fuchida's later claims, which sometimes conflict with documented historic records.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Genda, who opined during the planning for the attack that without an invasion three strikes were necessary to fully destroy the Pacific Fleet, denied requesting an additional attack.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Although a hypothetical third strike would have likely focused on the base's remaining warships, military historians have suggested any potential damage to the shore facilities would have hampered the Pacific Fleet far more seriously.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] If they had been wiped out, "serious [American] operations in the Pacific would have been postponed for more than a year"; according to Admiral Chester W.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Nimitz, later Commander in Chief of the Pacific Fleet, "it would have prolonged the war another two years".
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At a conference aboard his flagship the following morning, Yamamoto supported Nagumo's withdrawal without launching a third wave.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In retrospect, sparing the vital dockyards, maintenance shops, and the oil tank farm meant the United States could respond relatively quickly in the Pacific.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Yamamoto later regretted Nagumo's decision to withdraw and categorically stated it had been a great mistake not to order a third strike.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Twenty-one American ships were damaged or lost in the attack, of which all but three were repaired and returned to service.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Five of these battleships would, after major repair, participate in the last-ever battleship-on-battleship engagement at the Battle of Surigao Strait, which would result in several Japanese losses, including two battleships.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] After a systematic search for survivors, Captain Homer N.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Wallin was ordered to lead a formal salvage operation.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Around Pearl Harbor, divers from the Navy (shore and tenders), the Pearl Harbor Naval Shipyard, and civilian contractors (Pacific Bridge Company and others) began work on the ships that could be refloated.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] They patched holes, cleared debris, and pumped water out of ships.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Melvin Storer and other Navy divers worked inside the damaged ships.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Within six months, five battleships and two cruisers were patched or refloated so they could be sent to shipyards in Pearl Harbor and on the mainland for extensive repair.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Intensive salvage operations continued for another year, a total of some 20,000 man-hours under water.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] *Arizona* and the target ship *Utah* were too heavily damaged for salvage and remain where they were sunk, with *Arizona* becoming a war memorial.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] *Oklahoma*, while raised, was never repaired and capsized while under tow to the mainland in 1947.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] *Nevada* proved particularly difficult to raise and repair; two men involved in the operation died after inhaling poisonous gases that had accumulated in the ship's interior.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] When feasible, armament and equipment were removed from vessels too damaged to repair and put to use to improve the anti-aircraft defense of the harbor or installed aboard other craft.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The initial announcement of the attack on Pearl Harbor was made by the White House Press Secretary, Stephen Early, at 2:22 p.m.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Initial reports of the attack moved on news wires at approximately 2:25 p.m.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The first radio coverage (which, at the time, represented the earliest opportunity for ordinary people to learn of the attack) was on the CBS radio network's scheduled news program, *World News Today*, at 2:30 p.m.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] John Charles Daly read the initial report, then switched to London, where Robert Trout ad-libbed on the possible London reaction.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The first report on NBC cut into a play, a dramatization of *The Inspector-General*, at 2:33 p.m.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Eastern time and lasted only 21 seconds.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Unlike the later practice with major news stories, there were only brief interruptions of scheduled commercial programming.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] WNBT from New York was the only TV station that was regularly airing that day in the country, with the comedy movie *Millionaire Playboy*, which was scheduled for 3:30-4:30 PM, being interrupted with the news of the attack.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The other station known to cover the attacks was WCBW, also out of New York, where a special report on the attack was broadcast that evening.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] There are no recordings of either station's coverage, either visual or audio.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] At the time of the attack, the last three regular season National Football League games were happening.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Chicago Bears were playing the Chicago Cardinals at Comiskey Park; the Brooklyn Dodgers were playing the New York Giants at the Polo Grounds; and the Philadelphia Eagles were playing the Washington Redskins at Washington's Griffith Stadium.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] All three games were in progress as the attacks began, and no official announcements were made at any of the games concerning the attacks, with many fans finding out from phone calls placed at the stadium or from newsboys outside the stadium.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] However, throughout the Redskins game, happening in Washington, many military, government and diplomatic personnel were asked to call their offices or return to them.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Donovan, was paged to call his office immediately, and all military personnel were asked to return to their stations at the conclusion of the game.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The Washington game, thanks to the announcements and general curiosity of the happenings, ended in a near-empty stadium.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] A contemporaneous newspaper report compared the attack to the Battle of Port Arthur in which the Imperial Japanese Navy attacked the Imperial Russian Navy, triggering the Russo-Japanese War, 37 years prior.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] Modern writers have continued to note parallels between the attacks, albeit more dispassionately.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] News of the attack was first broadcast at 11:30 AM (Japanese Standard Time), however it had already been announced "shortly after" 7 AM (Japanese Standard Time) that Japan had "entered into a situation of war with the United States and Britain in the Western Pacific before dawn".
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] There was no further elaboration or explanation, and the attacks were already finished by that time.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The attack on Pearl Harbor was eventually covered in the Japanese press, but press in wartime Japan was heavily censored.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] One Japanese newspaper, *The* *Asahi Shimbun* did report on the attack the day it occurred, and from that point onward their editorials began to back governmental decisions regardless of what they were.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The *Asahi Shimbun* also reported the declaration of war on the United States after the attacks, framing it as an Imperial Order, with most Japanese people taking it that way.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] In contrast, coverage in *The New York Times* focused on "the danger to democracy and to the nation" brought on by the Japanese attack.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] NHK broadcast twelve special news reports along with its six regularly scheduled ones that day.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] NHK covered the news of Pearl Harbor and other attacks positively throughout the rest of the month.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p01] The United Kingdom's BBC broadcast news of the attack and that Manila was also under attack.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The day after the attack, US President Franklin D.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Roosevelt delivered his famous Day of Infamy speech to a Joint Session of Congress, calling for a formal declaration of war on the Empire of Japan.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Congress obliged his request less than an hour later.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] On December 11, Germany and Italy declared war on the United States, even though the Tripartite Pact did not require it.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Congress issued a declaration of war against Germany and Italy later that same day.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The United Kingdom had already been at war with Germany since September 1939 and with Italy since June 1940, and British Prime Minister Winston Churchill had promised to declare war "within the hour" of a Japanese attack on the United States.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Upon learning of the Japanese attacks on Malaya, Singapore, and Hong Kong, Churchill promptly determined there was no need to either wait or further consult the US government and immediately summoned the Japanese ambassador.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] As a result, the United Kingdom declared war on Japan nine hours before the United States did.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The attack was a shock to all the Allies in the Pacific Theater.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Further losses compounded the alarming setback.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Japan began the Philippines campaign (1941–1942) hours later (because of the time difference, it was December 8 in the Philippines).
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Only three days after the attack on Pearl Harbor, *Prince of Wales* and *Repulse* were sunk off Malaya.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Churchill recollected "In all the war I never received a more direct shock.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] As I turned and twisted in bed the full horror of the news sank in upon me.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] There were no British or American capital ships in the Indian Ocean or the Pacific except the American survivors of Pearl Harbor who were hastening back to California.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Throughout the war, Pearl Harbor was frequently used in American propaganda.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The bombing of Pearl Harbor would not persuade controversial Detroit area priest Charles Coughlin to support US entry into World War II, with Coughlin even alleging that Jews had planned the war for their own benefit and had conspired to involve the United States.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] One further consequence of the attack on Pearl Harbor and its aftermath (notably the Niʻihau incident) was that Japanese-American residents and citizens were imprisoned in nearby Japanese-American internment camps.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Within hours of the attack, hundreds of Japanese-American leaders were rounded up and taken to high-security camps such as Sand Island at the mouth of Honolulu harbor and Kilauea Military Camp on the island of Hawaii.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Eventually, more than 110,000 Japanese Americans, nearly all who lived on the West Coast, were forced into interior camps, but in Hawaii, where the 150,000-plus Japanese Americans composed over one-third of the population, only 1,200 to 1,800 were interned.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The attack also had international consequences.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The Canadian province of British Columbia, bordering the Pacific Ocean, had long had a large population of Japanese immigrants and their Japanese-Canadian descendants.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Pre-war tensions were exacerbated by the Pearl Harbor attack, leading to a reaction from the government of Canada.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] On February 24, 1942, Order-in-Council P.C. no.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] 1486 was issued under the War Measures Act, allowing for the forced removal of any and all Canadians of Japanese descent from British Columbia and prohibiting them from returning to the province.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] On March 4, regulations under the act were adopted to expel Japanese Canadians.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] As a result, 12,000 were interned in interior camps, 2,000 were sent to road camps, and another 2,000 were forced to work in the prairies on sugar beet farms.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Additionally, a special military award, the Pearl Harbor Commemorative Medal, was later authorized for all military veterans of the attack.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Japanese planners of the Pearl Harbor attack had determined that some means were required for rescuing fliers whose aircraft were damaged too badly to return to the carriers.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The island of Niʻihau, only thirty minutes by air from Pearl Harbor, was designated as the rescue point.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] During the second wave, a Zero fighter flown by Petty Officer Shigenori Nishikaichi of *Hiryu* was damaged in the attack on Wheeler, so he flew to the rescue point.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The aircraft was further damaged on his crash landing.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Nishikaichi was helped from the wreckage by one of the Native Hawaiians, who, aware of the tension between the United States and Japan, took the pilot's pistol, maps, codes and other documents.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The island's residents had no telephones or radios and were completely unaware of the attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Nishikaichi enlisted the support of three Japanese-American residents in an attempt to recover the documents.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] During the ensuing struggles, Nishikaichi was killed, and a Hawaiian civilian was wounded; one collaborator committed suicide, and his wife and the third collaborator were sent to prison.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The ease with which the local ethnic Japanese residents had apparently gone to Nishikaichi's assistance was a source of concern for many and tended to support those who believed that local Japanese could not be trusted.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] While the attack accomplished its intended objective, it turned out to be largely unnecessary.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Unknown to Yamamoto, who conceived the original plan, the United States Navy had decided as far back as 1935 to abandon "charging" across the Pacific towards the Philippines in response to an outbreak of war (in keeping with the evolution of Plan Orange).
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The United States instead adopted "Plan Dog" in 1940, which emphasized keeping the IJN out of the eastern Pacific and away from the shipping lanes to Australia, while the United States concentrated on defeating Nazi Germany.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Fortunately for the United States, the American aircraft carriers were untouched; otherwise, the Pacific Fleet's ability to conduct offensive operations would have been crippled for a year or more (given no diversions from the Atlantic Fleet).
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] As it was, the Navy was left with no choice but to rely on carriers and submarines.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] While six of the eight battleships were repaired and returned to service, their relatively low speed and high fuel consumption limited their deployment, and they served mainly in shore bombardment roles (their only major action being the Battle of Surigao Strait in October 1944).
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] A major flaw in Japanese strategic thinking was their reliance on *Kantai Kessen*, a belief that the ultimate Pacific battle would be fought by battleships, in keeping with the doctrine of Captain Alfred Thayer Mahan.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] As a result, Yamamoto (and his successors) hoarded battleships for a "decisive battle" that never happened.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The Japanese confidence in their ability to win a quick victory meant that they neglected Pearl Harbor's navy repair yards, oil tank farms, submarine base, and old headquarters building.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] All of these targets were omitted from Genda's list, yet they proved more important than any battleship to the American war effort in the Pacific.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The survival of the repair shops and fuel depots allowed Pearl Harbor to maintain logistical support of the Navy, such as the Doolittle Raid, the Battle of the Coral Sea, and the Battle of Midway.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Lastly, the basement of the Old Administration Building was the home of the cryptanalytic unit that contributed significantly to the Midway ambush and the submarine force's success.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The Japanese failure to follow up their attack on Pearl Harbor with an invasion of Hawaii was also seen as another strategic failure, although experts find it unlikely Japan could have pulled off such a feat.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Japan had long seen Hawaii as a part of their planned Pacific empire.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] As early as 1932 and even 1924, Admiral Seijiro Kawashima and Commander Hironori Mizuno argued that in the event of any war with the United States, Japan needed to take Hawaii, and a failure to do so would doom the war to being prolonged, and keep Japan from being able to win.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Before the Pearl Harbor attack, Japanese intelligence officer Kinoaki Matsuo and Japanese Commander Minuro Genda were both in favor of invading Hawaii, believing that such a move was necessary for forcing the US to the negotiating table and winning the war.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] However, in the wake of discussions following the war games drilling for the Pearl Harbor attack on 5–17 September 1941, Admiral Isoroku Yamamoto ultimately decided against attempting an invasion of Hawaii.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] On 9 December, two days after the attack, Admiral Yamamoto apparently changed his mind, and realizing the strategic blunder in failing to seize Oahu, decided to prepare plans for an invasion of Hawaii, which was dubbed the "Yamaguchi Plan".
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The plan consisted of seizing Midway Island, Johnston Atoll, and Palmyra Island, and imposing a tightening blockade on Oahu.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] After seizing the Big Island of Hawaii, Oahu would fall to an amphibious assault.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] However, Japan's decisive defeat at the Battle of Midway in June 1942 permanently scuttled those plans.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] There has been debate as to how and why the United States had been caught unaware, and how much and when American officials knew of Japanese plans and related topics.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] As early as 1924, Chief of United States Air Service Mason Patrick showed concern for military vulnerabilities in the Pacific, having sent General Billy Mitchell on a survey of the Pacific and the East.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Patrick called Mitchell's subsequent report, which identified vulnerabilities in Hawaii, a "theoretical treatise on employment of airpower in the Pacific, which, in all probability undoubtedly will be of extreme value some 10 or 15 years hence".
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] At least two naval war games, one in 1932 and another in 1936, proved that Pearl was vulnerable to such an attack.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Admiral James Richardson was removed from command shortly after protesting President Roosevelt's decision to move the bulk of the Pacific fleet to Pearl Harbor.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The decisions of military and political leadership to ignore these warnings have contributed to conspiracy theories.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] However, this conspiracy theory is rejected by mainstream historians.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The theory that the Americans were warned in advance, however, is supported by statements made by Dick Ellis, a British-Australian intelligence officer for MI6 who helped William J.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Donovan set up the Office of Strategic Services.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Ellis was deputy to William Stephenson at British Security Co-ordination.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] In Jesse Fink's 2023 biography of Ellis, *The Eagle in the Mirror*, Ellis is quoted as saying: "[Stephenson] was convinced from the information that was reaching him that this attack was imminent, and through Jimmy Roosevelt, President Roosevelt's son, he passed this information to the President.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] The US Navy's "Washington chief" during the Pearl Harbor attack was Admiral Harold R.
[src:conning-tower/attack-on-pearl-harbor-p02] Stark, who was the Chief of Naval Operations.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The **Battle of Kinburn**, a combined land-naval engagement during the final stage of the Crimean War, took place on the tip of the Kinburn Peninsula (on the south shore of the Dnieper–Bug estuary in what is now Ukraine) on 17 October 1855.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] During the battle a combined fleet of vessels from the French Navy and the British Royal Navy bombarded Russian coastal fortifications after an Anglo-French ground force had besieged them.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Three French ironclad batteries carried out the main attack, which saw the main Russian fortress destroyed in an action that lasted about three hours.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The battle, although strategically insignificant with little effect on the outcome of the war, is notable for the first use of modern ironclad warships in action.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Although frequently hit, the French ships destroyed the Russian forts within three hours, suffering minimal casualties in the process.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] This battle convinced contemporary navies to design and build new major warships with armour plating; this instigated a naval arms race between France and Britain lasting over a decade.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] In September 1854, the Anglo-French army that had been at Varna was ferried across the Black Sea and landed on the Crimean Peninsula.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] They then fought their way to the main Russian naval base on the peninsula, the city of Sevastopol, which they placed under siege.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The Russian garrison eventually withdrew from the city in early September 1855, freeing the French and British fleets for other tasks.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] A discussion ensued over what target should be attacked next; the French and British high commands considered driving from the Crimea to Kherson and launching major campaigns in Bessarabia or the Caucasus.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Instead, at the urging of French commanders, they settled on a smaller-scale operation to seize the Russian fort at Kinburn, which protected the mouth of the Dnieper.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The British argued that to seize Kinburn without advancing to Nikolaev would only serve to warn the Russians of the threat to the port.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Fox Maule-Ramsay, then the British Secretary of State for War, suggested that without a plan to exploit the capture of the fortress, the only purpose of the operation would be to give the fleets something to do.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The fortress was located on the Kinburn Spit, at the extreme western end of the Kinburn Peninsula, and consisted of three separate fortifications.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The primary fort, built of stone, square, and equipped with bastions, held 50 guns, some of which were mounted in protective casemates; the rest were in *en barbette* mountings, firing over the parapets.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Two smaller fortresses were located further down the spit, mounting ten and eleven guns, respectively.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The first was a small stone fort, while the second was a simple sand earthwork.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The forts were armed only with medium and smaller calibre guns, the largest guns being 24-pounders.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Major General Maxim Kokhanovitch commanded the garrison of 1,500 men, most of whom were stationed in the main fort.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Across the estuary was Fort Nikolaev in the town of Ochakov with fifteen more guns, but these were too far away to play a role in the battle.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] To attack the forts, the British and French assembled a fleet centred on four French and six British ships of the line, led by British Rear Admiral Edmund Lyons and the French Vice Admiral Armand Joseph Bruat.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The British contributed a further seventeen frigates and sloops, ten gunboats, and six bomb vessels, along with ten transport vessels.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The French squadron included three corvettes, four avisos, twelve gunboats, and five bomb vessels.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The transports carried a force of 8,000 men from French and British Army regiments that would be used to besiege the forts.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] In addition to the contingent of conventional sailing warships, the French squadron brought three experimental ironclad warships that had recently arrived from France.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] These, the first three ironclad batteries of the *Dévastation* class—*Lave*, *Dévastation*, and *Tonnante*—had been sent to the Black Sea in late July, but they arrived too late to take part in the siege of Sevastopol.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] These vessels, the first ironclad warships, carried eighteen 50-pounder guns and were protected with 4 inches (100 mm) of wrought iron armour.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] Observers speculated that these untested warships would be ineffective in combat, owing to their slow speed and poor handling.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] In an effort to confuse the Russians, the combined fleet made a feint westward toward Odessa on 8 October before turning east to Kinburn.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] The combined French and British fleet arrived off Kinburn on 14 October.
[src:conning-tower/battle-of-kinburn-1855] That night, a force of nine gunboats escorted transports carrying 8,000 men, led by François Achille Bazaine, who were landed behind the forts, further up the peninsula.
